[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The SI unit of both stress tensor and traction vector is the newton per square metre (N/m2) or pascal (Pa), corresponding to the stress scalar.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The Cauchy stress tensor obeys the tensor transformation law under a change in the system of coordinates.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] A graphical representation of two-dimensional coordinate transformations Mohr's circle for stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The Cauchy stress tensor is used for stress analysis of material bodies experiencing small deformations: it is a central concept in the linear theory of elasticity.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] For large deformations, also called finite deformations, other measures of stress are required, such as the Piola–Kirchhoff stress tensor, the Biot stress tensor, and the Kirchhoff stress tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] However, in the presence of couple-stresses, i.e. moments per unit volume, the stress tensor is non-symmetric.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] This also is the case when the Knudsen number is close to one, ⁠ $K_{n}\rightarrow 1$ ⁠, or the continuum is a non-Newtonian fluid, which can lead to rotationally non-invariant fluids, such as polymers.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] There are certain invariants associated with the stress tensor, whose values do not depend upon the coordinate system chosen, or the area element upon which the stress tensor operates.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] These are the three eigenvalues of the stress tensor, which are called the principal stresses.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Following the classical dynamics of Newton and Euler, the motion of a material body is produced by the action of externally applied forces which are assumed to be of two kinds: surface forces $\mathbf {F}$ and body forces ⁠ $\mathbf {b}$ ⁠.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Only surface forces will be discussed in this article as they are relevant to the Cauchy stress tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] On an element of area $\Delta S$ containing P , with normal vector ⁠ $\mathbf {n}$ ⁠, the force distribution is equipollent to a contact force $\Delta \mathbf {F}$ exerted at point P and surface moment $\Delta \mathbf {M}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] where $\mathbf {T} ^{(\mathbf {n} )}$ is the *mean surface traction*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Cauchy's stress principle asserts that as $\Delta S$ tends to zero the ratio $\Delta \mathbf {F} /\Delta S$ becomes $d\mathbf {F} /dS$ and the couple stress vector $\Delta \mathbf {M}$ vanishes.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] In specific fields of continuum mechanics the couple stress is assumed not to vanish; however, classical branches of continuum mechanics address non-polar materials which do not consider couple stresses and body moments.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] This equation means that the stress vector depends on its location in the body and the orientation of the plane on which it is acting.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] It is not a vector field because it depends not only on the position $\mathbf {x}$ of a particular material point, but also on the local orientation of the surface element as defined by its normal vector ⁠ $\mathbf {n}$ ⁠.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The shear stress can be further decomposed into two mutually perpendicular vectors.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] According to the *Cauchy Postulate*, the stress vector $\mathbf {T} ^{(\mathbf {n} )}$ remains unchanged for all surfaces passing through the point P and having the same normal vector $\mathbf {n}$ at ⁠ P ⁠, i.e., having a common tangent at ⁠ P ⁠.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] This means that the stress vector is a function of the normal vector $\mathbf {n}$ only, and is not influenced by the curvature of the internal surfaces.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] A consequence of Cauchy's postulate is *Cauchy's Fundamental Lemma*, also called the *Cauchy reciprocal theorem*, which states that the stress vectors acting on opposite sides of the same surface are equal in magnitude and opposite in direction.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] To prove this expression, consider a tetrahedron with three faces oriented in the coordinate planes, and with an infinitesimal area d*A* oriented in an arbitrary direction specified by a normal unit vector **n** (Figure 2.2).
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The tetrahedron is formed by slicing the infinitesimal element along an arbitrary plane with unit normal **n**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The stress vector on this plane is denoted by **T**(**n**).
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The stress vectors acting on the faces of the tetrahedron are denoted as **T**(**e**1), **T**(**e**2), and **T**(**e**3), and are by definition the components *σij* of the stress tensor **σ**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] This tetrahedron is sometimes called the *Cauchy tetrahedron*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] where the right-hand-side represents the product of the mass enclosed by the tetrahedron and its acceleration: *ρ* is the density, **a** is the acceleration, and *h* is the height of the tetrahedron, considering the plane **n** as the base.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] To consider the limiting case as the tetrahedron shrinks to a point, *h* must go to 0 (intuitively, the plane **n** is translated along **n** toward *O*).
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] A stress component is positive if it acts in the positive direction of the coordinate axes, and if the plane where it acts has an outward normal vector pointing in the positive coordinate direction.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The Voigt notation is used extensively in representing stress–strain relations in solid mechanics and for computational efficiency in numerical structural mechanics software.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] It can be shown that the stress tensor is a contravariant second order tensor, which is a statement of how it transforms under a change of the coordinate system.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] where **A** is a rotation matrix with components *aij*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The Mohr circle for stress is a graphical representation of this transformation of stresses.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] where p is the hydrostatic pressure, and ${\delta _{ij}}\$ is the Kronecker delta.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The three stresses normal to these principal planes are called *principal stresses*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The components $\sigma _{ij}$ of the stress tensor depend on the orientation of the coordinate system at the point under consideration.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] However, the stress tensor itself is a physical quantity and as such, it is independent of the coordinate system chosen to represent it.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] There are certain invariants associated with every tensor which are also independent of the coordinate system.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] For example, a vector is a simple tensor of rank one.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] In three dimensions, it has three components.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The value of these components will depend on the coordinate system chosen to represent the vector, but the magnitude of the vector is a physical quantity (a scalar) and is independent of the Cartesian coordinate system chosen to represent the vector (so long as it is normal).
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Similarly, every second rank tensor (such as the stress and the strain tensors) has three independent invariant quantities associated with it.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] One set of such invariants are the principal stresses of the stress tensor, which are just the eigenvalues of the stress tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Their direction vectors are the principal directions or eigenvectors.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] where $\lambda$ is a constant of proportionality, and in this particular case corresponds to the magnitudes $\sigma _{\mathrm {n} }$ of the normal stress vectors or principal stresses.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] This is a homogeneous system, i.e. equal to zero, of three linear equations where $n_{j}$ are the unknowns.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] To obtain a nontrivial (non-zero) solution for ⁠ $n_{j}$ ⁠, the matrix determinant of the coefficients must be equal to zero, i.e. the system is singular.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The characteristic equation has three real roots $\lambda _{i}$ (i.e. with a zero imaginary component) due to the stress tensor being symmetric.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The eigenvalues are the roots of the characteristic polynomial.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The principal stresses are unique for a given stress tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Therefore, from the characteristic equation, the coefficients $I_{1}$ , $I_{2}$ and $I_{3}$ , called the first, second, and third *stress invariants*, respectively, always have the same value regardless of the coordinate system's orientation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] For each eigenvalue, there is a non-trivial solution for $n_{j}$ in the equation ⁠ $\left(\sigma _{ij}-\lambda \delta _{ij}\right)n_{j}=0$ ⁠.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] These solutions are the principal directions or eigenvectors defining the plane where the principal stresses act.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The principal stresses and principal directions characterize the stress at a point and are independent of the orientation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The principal stresses can be combined to form the stress invariants, ⁠ $I_{1}$ ⁠, ⁠ $I_{2}$ ⁠, and ⁠ $I_{3}$ ⁠.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The first and third invariant are the trace and determinant respectively, of the stress tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Because of its simplicity, the principal coordinate system is often useful when considering the state of the elastic medium at a particular point.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Principal stresses are often expressed in the following equation for evaluating stresses in the x and y directions or axial and bending stresses on a part.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The principal normal stresses can then be used to calculate the von Mises stress and ultimately the safety factor and margin of safety.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Using just the part of the equation under the square root is equal to the maximum and minimum shear stress for plus and minus.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] 2. a deviatoric component called the *stress deviator tensor*, ⁠ $s_{ij}$ ⁠, which tends to distort it.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Pressure (⁠ p ⁠) is generally defined as negative one-third the trace of the stress tensor minus any stress the divergence of the velocity contributes with, i.e.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] where $\zeta$ is a proportionality constant (viz. the Volume viscosity), $\nabla \cdot$ is the divergence operator, $x_{k}$ is the *k*th Cartesian coordinate, ${\vec {u}}$ is the flow velocity and $u_{k}$ is the *k*th Cartesian component of ⁠ ${\vec {u}}$ ⁠.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] As it is a second order tensor, the stress deviator tensor also has a set of invariants, which can be obtained using the same procedure used to calculate the invariants of the stress tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] It can be shown that the principal directions of the stress deviator tensor $s_{ij}$ are the same as the principal directions of the stress tensor ⁠ $\sigma _{ij}$ ⁠.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] where ⁠ $J_{1}$ ⁠, $J_{2}$ and $J_{3}$ are the first, second, and third *deviatoric stress invariants*, respectively.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Their values are the same (invariant) regardless of the orientation of the coordinate system chosen.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] These deviatoric stress invariants can be expressed as a function of the components of $s_{ij}$ or its principal values $s_{1}$ , $s_{2}$ , and $s_{3}$ , or alternatively, as a function of $\sigma _{ij}$ or its principal values ⁠ $\sigma _{1}$ ⁠, ⁠ $\sigma _{2}$ ⁠, and ⁠ $\sigma _{3}$ ⁠.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Because ⁠ $s_{kk}=0$ ⁠, the stress deviator tensor is in a state of pure shear.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] A quantity called the equivalent stress or von Mises stress is commonly used in solid mechanics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Considering the principal directions as the coordinate axes, a plane whose normal vector makes equal angles with each of the principal axes (i.e. having direction cosines equal to ⁠ $\vert 1/{\sqrt {3}}\vert$ ⁠) is called an *octahedral plane*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] There are a total of eight octahedral planes (Figure 6).
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] The normal and shear components of the stress tensor on these planes are called *octahedral normal stress* $\sigma _{\text{oct}}$ and *octahedral shear stress* ⁠ $\tau _{\text{oct}}$ ⁠, respectively.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] Octahedral plane passing through the origin is known as the *π-plane* (*π* not to be confused with *mean stress* denoted by *π* in above section) *.* On the *π-plane*, ⁠ $\textstyle s_{ij}={\frac {1}{3}}I$ ⁠.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] which is the mean normal stress or hydrostatic stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/cauchy-stress-tensor] This value is the same in all eight octahedral planes.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Some constitutive equations are simply phenomenological; others are derived from first principles.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] A common approximate constitutive equation frequently is expressed as a simple proportionality using a parameter taken to be a property of the material, such as electrical conductivity or a spring constant.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] However, it is often necessary to account for the directional dependence of the material, and the scalar parameter is generalized to a tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Constitutive relations are also modified to account for the rate of response of materials and their non-linear behavior.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] See the article Linear response function.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The first constitutive equation (constitutive law) was developed by Robert Hooke and is known as Hooke's law.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] It deals with the case of linear elastic materials.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Following this discovery, this type of equation, often called a "stress-strain relation" in this example, but also called a "constitutive assumption" or an "equation of state" was commonly used.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Walter Noll advanced the use of constitutive equations, clarifying their classification and the role of invariance requirements, constraints, and definitions of terms like "material", "isotropic", "aeolotropic", etc.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The class of "constitutive relations" of the form *stress rate* = f (velocity *gradient*, *stress*, *density*) was the subject of Walter Noll's dissertation in 1954 under Clifford Truesdell.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] In modern condensed matter physics, the constitutive equation plays a major role.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] See Linear constitutive equations and Nonlinear correlation functions.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The stress-strain constitutive relation for linear materials is commonly known as Hooke's law.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] where C is the elasticity tensor and S is the compliance tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The applied force induces non-recoverable deformation in the material when the stress (or elastic strain) reaches a critical magnitude, called the yield point.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The material recovers its initial shape after deformation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] If the time-dependent resistive contributions are large, and cannot be neglected.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Rubbers and plastics have this property, and certainly do not satisfy Hooke's law.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] If the material is close to elastic, but the applied force induces additional time-dependent resistive forces (i.e. depend on rate of change of extension/compression, in addition to the extension/compression).
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Metals and ceramics have this characteristic, but it is usually negligible, although not so much when heating due to friction occurs (such as vibrations or shear stresses in machines).
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] which depends on the materials A and B are made from, since the collision involves interactions at the surfaces of A and B.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Usually 0 ≤ *e* ≤ 1, in which *e* = 1 for completely elastic collisions, and *e* = 0 for completely inelastic collisions.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] It is possible for *e* ≥ 1 to occur – for superelastic (or explosive) collisions.
