[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] For a Newtonian fluid of viscosity μ, the shear stress τ is linearly related to the strain rate (transverse flow velocity gradient) ∂*u*/∂*y* (units *s*−1).
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] with *u*(*y*) the variation of the flow velocity u in the cross-flow (transverse) direction y.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] where R is the gas constant (J⋅K−1⋅mol−1).
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] In both classical and quantum physics, the precise dynamics of a system form a set of coupled differential equations, which are almost always too complicated to be solved exactly, even at the level of statistical mechanics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] In the context of electromagnetism, this remark applies to not only the dynamics of free charges and currents (which enter Maxwell's equations directly), but also the dynamics of bound charges and currents (which enter Maxwell's equations through the constitutive relations).
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] As a result, various approximation schemes are typically used.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] For example, in real materials, complex transport equations must be solved to determine the time and spatial response of charges, for example, the Boltzmann equation or the Fokker–Planck equation or the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] For example, see magnetohydrodynamics, fluid dynamics, electrohydrodynamics, superconductivity, plasma modeling.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] An entire physical apparatus for dealing with these matters has developed.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] See for example, linear response theory, Green–Kubo relations and Green's function (many-body theory).
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] These complex theories provide detailed formulas for the constitutive relations describing the electrical response of various materials, such as permittivities, permeabilities, conductivities and so forth.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] It is necessary to specify the relations between displacement field **D** and **E**, and the magnetic H-field **H** and **B**, before doing calculations in electromagnetism (i.e. applying Maxwell's macroscopic equations).
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] These equations specify the response of bound charge and current to the applied fields and are called constitutive relations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] where **P** is the polarization field and **M** is the magnetization field which are defined in terms of microscopic bound charges and bound current respectively.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Before getting to how to calculate **M** and **P** it is useful to examine the following special cases.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] where *ε*0 and *μ*0 are two universal constants, called the permittivity of free space and permeability of free space, respectively.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] In an (isotropic) linear material, where **P** is proportional to **E**, and **M** is proportional to **B**, the constitutive relations are also straightforward.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] where *χ*e and *χ*m are the electric and magnetic susceptibilities of a given material respectively.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] where ε and μ are constants (which depend on the material), called the permittivity and permeability, respectively, of the material.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] For real-world materials, the constitutive relations are not linear, except approximately.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Calculating the constitutive relations from first principles involves determining how **P** and **M** are created from a given **E** and **B**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] These relations may be empirical (based directly upon measurements), or theoretical (based upon statistical mechanics, transport theory or other tools of condensed matter physics).
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The detail employed may be macroscopic or microscopic, depending upon the level necessary to the problem under scrutiny.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] In general, the constitutive relations can usually still be written: $\mathbf {D} =\varepsilon \mathbf {E} ,\quad \mathbf {H} =\mu ^{-1}\mathbf {B}$ but ε and μ are not, in general, simple constants, but rather functions of **E**, **B**, position and time, and tensorial in nature.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] In practice, some materials properties have a negligible impact in particular circumstances, permitting neglect of small effects.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Some man-made materials such as metamaterials and photonic crystals are designed to have customized permittivity and permeability.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The theoretical calculation of a material's constitutive equations is a common, important, and sometimes difficult task in theoretical condensed-matter physics and materials science.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] In general, the constitutive equations are theoretically determined by calculating how a molecule responds to the local fields through the Lorentz force.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Other forces may need to be modeled as well such as lattice vibrations in crystals or bond forces.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Including all of the forces leads to changes in the molecule which are used to calculate **P** and **M** as a function of the local fields.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The local fields differ from the applied fields due to the fields produced by the polarization and magnetization of nearby material; an effect which also needs to be modeled.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] Further, real materials are not continuous media; the local fields of real materials vary wildly on the atomic scale.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The fields need to be averaged over a suitable volume to form a continuum approximation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] These continuum approximations often require some type of quantum mechanical analysis such as quantum field theory as applied to condensed matter physics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] See, for example, density functional theory, Green–Kubo relations and Green's function.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The theoretical modeling of the continuum-approximation properties of many real materials often rely upon experimental measurement as well.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] For example, ε of an insulator at low frequencies can be measured by making it into a parallel-plate capacitor, and ε at optical-light frequencies is often measured by ellipsometry.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] These constitutive equations are often used in crystallography, a field of solid-state physics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] where ε is the permittivity and *ε*r the relative permittivity of the medium, likewise μ is the permeability and *μ*r are the relative permeability of the medium.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The vacuum permittivity is *ε*0 and vacuum permeability is *μ*0.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] In general, n (also *ε*r) are complex numbers.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] The relative refractive index is defined as the ratio of the two refractive indices.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] There are several laws which describe the transport of matter, or properties of it, in an almost identical way.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] , the constant of proportionality is the characteristic of the material.
[src:continuum-mechanics/constitutive-equation] In general the constant must be replaced by a 2nd rank tensor, to account for directional dependences of the material.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Continuum mechanics deals with *deformable bodies*, as opposed to rigid bodies.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] A continuum model assumes that the substance of the object completely fills the space it occupies.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] While ignoring the fact that matter is made of atoms, this provides a sufficiently accurate description of matter on length scales much greater than that of inter-atomic distances.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The concept of a continuous medium allows for intuitive analysis of bulk matter by using differential equations that describe the behavior of such matter according to physical laws, such as mass conservation, momentum conservation, and energy conservation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Information about the specific material is expressed in constitutive relationships.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Continuum mechanics treats the physical properties of solids and fluids independently of any particular coordinate system in which they are observed.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] These properties are represented by tensors, which are mathematical objects with the salient property of being independent of coordinate systems.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] This permits definition of physical properties at any point in the continuum, according to mathematically convenient continuous functions.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The theories of elasticity, plasticity and fluid mechanics are based on the concepts of continuum mechanics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The concept of a continuum underlies the mathematical framework for studying large-scale forces and deformations in materials.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Although materials are composed of discrete atoms and molecules, separated by empty space or microscopic cracks and crystallographic defects, physical phenomena can often be modeled by considering a substance distributed throughout some region of space.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] A continuum is a body that can be continually sub-divided into infinitesimal elements with local material properties defined at any particular point.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Properties of the bulk material can therefore be described by almost everywhere smooth functions of position in the continuum, and their evolution with time can be studied using calculus.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Apart from the assumption of continuity, two other independent assumptions are often employed in the study of continuum mechanics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] These are homogeneity (assumption of identical properties at all locations) and isotropy (assumption of directionally invariant vector properties).
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] If these auxiliary assumptions are not globally applicable, the material may be segregated into sections where they are applicable in order to simplify the analysis.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] For more complex cases, one or both of these assumptions can be dropped.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In these cases, computational methods are often used to solve the differential equations describing the evolution of material properties.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] An additional area of continuum mechanics comprises elastomeric foams, which exhibit a curious hyperbolic stress-strain relationship.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The elastomer is a true continuum, but a homogeneous distribution of voids gives it unusual properties.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Continuum mechanics models begin by assigning a region in three-dimensional Euclidean space to the material body ${\mathcal {B}}$ being modeled.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The points within this region are called particles or material points.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Different *configurations* or states of the body correspond to different regions in Euclidean space.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The region corresponding to the body's configuration at time t is labeled $\kappa _{t}({\mathcal {B}})$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] where $\mathbf {e} _{i}$ are the coordinate vectors in some frame of reference chosen for the problem (See figure 1).
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] For the mathematical formulation of the model, $\kappa _{t}(\cdot )$ is also assumed to be twice continuously differentiable, so that differential equations describing the motion may be formulated.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] A solid is a deformable body that possesses shear strength, *sc.* a solid can support shear forces (forces parallel to the material surface on which they act).
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Fluids, on the other hand, do not sustain shear forces.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Following the classical dynamics of Isaac Newton and Leonhard Euler, the motion of a material body is produced by the action of externally applied forces which are assumed to be of two kinds: surface forces $\mathbf {F} _{C}$ and body forces $\mathbf {F} _{B}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The distribution of internal contact forces throughout the volume of the body is assumed to be continuous.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Therefore, there exists a *contact force density* or *Cauchy traction field* $\mathbf {T} (\mathbf {n} ,\mathbf {x} ,t)$ that represents this distribution in a particular configuration of the body at a given time $t\,\!$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] It is not a vector field because it depends not only on the position $\mathbf {x}$ of a particular material point, but also on the local orientation of the surface element as defined by its normal vector $\mathbf {n}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] where $\mathbf {T} ^{(\mathbf {n} )}$ is the *surface traction*, also called *stress vector*, *traction*, or *traction vector*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The stress vector is a frame-indifferent vector (see Euler-Cauchy's stress principle).
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In continuum mechanics a body is considered stress-free if the only forces present are those inter-atomic forces (ionic, metallic, and van der Waals forces) required to hold the body together and to keep its shape in the absence of all external influences, including gravitational attraction.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Stresses generated during manufacture of the body to a specific configuration are also excluded when considering stresses in a body.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Therefore, the stresses considered in continuum mechanics are only those produced by deformation of the body, *sc.* only relative changes in stress are considered, not the absolute values of stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In the case of gravitational forces, the intensity of the force depends on, or is proportional to, the mass density $\mathbf {\rho } (\mathbf {x} ,t)\,\!$ of the material, and it is specified in terms of force per unit mass ( $b_{i}\,\!$ ) or per unit volume ( $p_{i}\,\!$ ).
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] These two specifications are related through the material density by the equation $\rho b_{i}=p_{i}\,\!$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Similarly, the intensity of electromagnetic forces depends upon the strength (electric charge) of the electromagnetic field.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Body forces and contact forces acting on the body lead to corresponding moments of force (torques) relative to a given point.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In certain situations, not commonly considered in the analysis of the mechanical behavior of materials, it becomes necessary to include two other types of forces: these are *couple stresses* (surface couples, contact torques) and *body moments*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Couple stresses are moments per unit area applied on a surface.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Body moments, or body couples, are moments per unit volume or per unit mass applied to the volume of the body.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Both are important in the analysis of stress for a polarized dielectric solid under the action of an electric field, materials where the molecular structure is taken into consideration (*e.g.* bones), solids under the action of an external magnetic field, and the dislocation theory of metals.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Materials that exhibit body couples and couple stresses in addition to moments produced exclusively by forces are called *polar materials*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] *Non-polar materials* are then those materials with only moments of forces.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In the classical branches of continuum mechanics the development of the theory of stresses is based on non-polar materials.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] A change in the configuration of a continuum body results in a displacement.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The displacement of a body has two components: a rigid-body displacement and a deformation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] A rigid-body displacement consists of a simultaneous translation and rotation of the body without changing its shape or size.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Deformation implies the change in shape and/or size of the body from an initial or undeformed configuration $\kappa _{0}({\mathcal {B}})$ to a current or deformed configuration $\kappa _{t}({\mathcal {B}})$ (Figure 2).
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The motion of a continuum body is a continuous time sequence of displacements.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Thus, the material body will occupy different configurations at different times so that a particle occupies a series of points in space which describe a path line.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] It is convenient to identify a reference configuration or initial condition which all subsequent configurations are referenced from.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The reference configuration need not be one that the body will ever occupy.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Often, the configuration at $t=0$ is considered the reference configuration, $\kappa _{0}({\mathcal {B}})$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The components $X_{i}$ of the position vector $\mathbf {X}$ of a particle, taken with respect to the reference configuration, are called the material or reference coordinates.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] When analyzing the motion or deformation of solids, or the flow of fluids, it is necessary to describe the sequence or evolution of configurations throughout time.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] One description for motion is made in terms of the material or referential coordinates, called material description or Lagrangian description.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In the Lagrangian description the position and physical properties of the particles are described in terms of the material or referential coordinates and time.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In this case **the reference configuration is the configuration at $t=0$**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] An observer standing in the frame of reference observes the changes in the position and physical properties as the material body moves in space as time progresses.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The results obtained are independent of the choice of initial time and reference configuration, $\kappa _{0}({\mathcal {B}})$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] This description is normally used in solid mechanics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The components $x_{i}$ are called the spatial coordinates.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Physical and kinematic properties $P_{ij\ldots }$ , i.e. thermodynamic properties and flow velocity, which describe or characterize features of the material body, are expressed as continuous functions of position and time, i.e. $P_{ij\ldots }=P_{ij\ldots }(\mathbf {X} ,t)$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The material derivative of any property $P_{ij\ldots }$ of a continuum, which may be a scalar, vector, or tensor, is the time rate of change of that property for a specific group of particles of the moving continuum body.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The material derivative is also known as the *substantial derivative*, or *comoving derivative*, or *convective derivative*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] It can be thought as the rate at which the property changes when measured by an observer traveling with that group of particles.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In the Lagrangian description, the material derivative of $P_{ij\ldots }$ is simply the partial derivative with respect to time, and the position vector $\mathbf {X}$ is held constant as it does not change with time.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The instantaneous position $\mathbf {x}$ is a property of a particle, and its material derivative is the *instantaneous flow velocity* $\mathbf {v}$ of the particle.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Continuity in the Lagrangian description is expressed by the spatial and temporal continuity of the mapping from the reference configuration to the current configuration of the material points.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] All physical quantities characterizing the continuum are described this way.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In this sense, the function $\chi (\cdot )$ and $P_{ij\ldots }(\cdot )$ are single-valued and continuous, with continuous derivatives with respect to space and time to whatever order is required, usually to the second or third.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Continuity allows for the inverse of $\chi (\cdot )$ to trace backwards where the particle currently located at $\mathbf {x}$ was located in the initial or referenced configuration $\kappa _{0}({\mathcal {B}})$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In this case the description of motion is made in terms of the spatial coordinates, in which case is called the spatial description or Eulerian description, i.e.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] **the current configuration is taken as the reference configuration**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The Eulerian description, focuses on the current configuration $\kappa _{t}({\mathcal {B}})$ , giving attention to what is occurring at a fixed point in space as time progresses, instead of giving attention to individual particles as they move through space and time.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] This approach is conveniently applied in the study of fluid flow where the kinematic property of greatest interest is the rate at which change is taking place rather than the shape of the body of fluid at a reference time.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] which provides a tracing of the particle which now occupies the position $\mathbf {x}$ in the current configuration $\kappa _{t}({\mathcal {B}})$ to its original position $\mathbf {X}$ in the initial configuration $\kappa _{0}({\mathcal {B}})$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] A necessary and sufficient condition for this inverse function to exist is that the determinant of the Jacobian matrix, often referred to simply as the Jacobian, should be different from zero.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] where the functional form of $P_{ij\ldots }$ in the Lagrangian description is not the same as the form of $p_{ij\ldots }$ in the Eulerian description.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The first term on the right-hand side of this equation gives the *local rate of change* of the property $p_{ij\ldots }(\mathbf {x} ,t)$ occurring at position $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The second term of the right-hand side is the *convective rate of change* and expresses the contribution of the particle changing position in space (motion).
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Continuity in the Eulerian description is expressed by the spatial and temporal continuity and continuous differentiability of the flow velocity field.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] All physical quantities are defined this way at each instant of time, in the current configuration, as a function of the vector position $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] A *displacement field* is a vector field of all displacement vectors for all particles in the body, which relates the deformed configuration with the undeformed configuration.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] where $\alpha _{Ji}$ are the direction cosines between the material and spatial coordinate systems with unit vectors $\mathbf {E} _{J}$ and $\mathbf {e} _{i}$ , respectively.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] It is common to superimpose the coordinate systems for the undeformed and deformed configurations, which results in $\mathbf {b} =0$ , and the direction cosines become Kronecker deltas, i.e.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Continuum mechanics deals with the behavior of materials that can be approximated as continuous for certain length and time scales.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The equations that govern the mechanics of such materials include the balance laws for mass, momentum, and energy.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Kinematic relations and constitutive equations are needed to complete the system of governing equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Physical restrictions on the form of the constitutive relations can be applied by requiring that the second law of thermodynamics be satisfied under all conditions.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In the continuum mechanics of solids, the second law of thermodynamics is satisfied if the Clausius–Duhem form of the entropy inequality is satisfied.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] 3. there is a source of the physical quantity inside the volume.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Let $\Omega$ be the body (an open subset of Euclidean space) and let $\partial \Omega$ be its surface (the boundary of $\Omega$ ).
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] where $\mathbf {X}$ is the position of a point in the initial configuration and $\mathbf {x}$ is the location of the same point in the deformed configuration.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Let $f(\mathbf {x} ,t)$ be a physical quantity that is flowing through the body.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Let $g(\mathbf {x} ,t)$ be sources on the surface of the body and let $h(\mathbf {x} ,t)$ be sources inside the body.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Let $\mathbf {n} (\mathbf {x} ,t)$ be the outward unit normal to the surface $\partial \Omega$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Let $\mathbf {v} (\mathbf {x} ,t)$ be the flow velocity of the physical particles that carry the physical quantity that is flowing.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Also, let the speed at which the bounding surface $\partial \Omega$ is moving be $u_{n}$ (in the direction $\mathbf {n}$ ).
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The functions $f(\mathbf {x} ,t)$ , $g(\mathbf {x} ,t)$ , and $h(\mathbf {x} ,t)$ can be scalar valued, vector valued, or tensor valued - depending on the physical quantity that the balance equation deals with.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] If there are internal boundaries in the body, jump discontinuities also need to be specified in the balance laws.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] In the above, ${\boldsymbol {P}}$ is the first Piola-Kirchhoff stress tensor, and $\rho _{0}$ is the mass density in the reference configuration.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] where $\mathbf {v}$ is a vector field, ${\boldsymbol {S}}$ is a second-order tensor field, and $\mathbf {e} _{i}$ are the components of an orthonormal basis in the current configuration.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] where $\mathbf {v}$ is a vector field, ${\boldsymbol {S}}$ is a second-order tensor field, and $\mathbf {E} _{i}$ are the components of an orthonormal basis in the reference configuration.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The Clausius–Duhem inequality can be used to express the second law of thermodynamics for elastic-plastic materials.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] This inequality is a statement concerning the irreversibility of natural processes, especially when energy dissipation is involved.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Just like in the balance laws in the previous section, we assume that there is a flux of a quantity, a source of the quantity, and an internal density of the quantity per unit mass.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The quantity of interest in this case is the entropy.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Thus, we assume that there is an entropy flux, an entropy source, an internal mass density $\rho$ and an internal specific entropy (i.e. entropy per unit mass) $\eta$ in the region of interest.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Let $\Omega$ be such a region and let $\partial \Omega$ be its boundary.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Let $\partial \Omega$ move with a flow velocity $u_{n}$ and let particles inside $\Omega$ have velocities $\mathbf {v}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Let $\mathbf {n}$ be the unit outward normal to the surface $\partial \Omega$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Let $\rho$ be the density of matter in the region, ${\bar {q}}$ be the entropy flux at the surface, and r be the entropy source per unit mass.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The scalar entropy flux can be related to the vector flux at the surface by the relation ${\bar {q}}=-{\boldsymbol {\psi }}(\mathbf {x} )\cdot \mathbf {n}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] where $\mathbf {q}$ is the heat flux vector, s is an energy source per unit mass, and T is the absolute temperature of a material point at $\mathbf {x}$ at time t .
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The validity of the continuum assumption may be verified by a theoretical analysis, in which either some clear periodicity is identified or statistical homogeneity and ergodicity of the microstructure exist.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] More specifically, the continuum hypothesis hinges on the concepts of a representative elementary volume and separation of scales based on the Hill–Mandel condition.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] This condition provides a link between an experimentalist's and a theoretician's viewpoint on constitutive equations (linear and nonlinear elastic/inelastic or coupled fields) as well as a way of spatial and statistical averaging of the microstructure.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] When the separation of scales does not hold, or when one wants to establish a continuum of a finer resolution than the size of the representative volume element (RVE), a statistical volume element (SVE) is employed, which results in random continuum fields.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The latter then provide a micromechanics basis for stochastic finite elements (SFE).
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] The levels of SVE and RVE link continuum mechanics to statistical mechanics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/continuum-mechanics] Experimentally, the RVE can only be evaluated when the constitutive response is spatially homogenous.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] In physics and continuum mechanics, **deformation** is the change in the shape or size of an object.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] It has dimension of length with SI unit of metre (m).
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] It is quantified as the residual displacement of particles in a non-rigid body, from an *initial* configuration to a *final* configuration, excluding the body's average translation and rotation (its rigid transformation).
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] A *configuration* is a set containing the positions of all particles of the body.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] A deformation can occur because of external loads, intrinsic activity (e.g. muscle contraction), body forces (such as gravity or electromagnetic forces), or changes in temperature, moisture content, or chemical reactions, etc.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] In a continuous body, a *deformation field* results from a stress field due to applied forces or because of some changes in the conditions of the body.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] The relation between stress and strain (relative deformation) is expressed by constitutive equations, e.g., Hooke's law for linear elastic materials.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Deformations which cease to exist after the stress field is removed are termed as **elastic deformation**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] In this case, the continuum completely recovers its original configuration.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] On the other hand, irreversible deformations may remain, and these exist even after stresses have been removed.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] One type of irreversible deformation is **plastic deformation**, which occurs in material bodies after stresses have attained a certain threshold value known as the *elastic limit* or yield stress, and are the result of slip, or dislocation mechanisms at the atomic level.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Another type of irreversible deformation is **viscous deformation**, which is the irreversible part of viscoelastic deformation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] In the case of elastic deformations, the response function linking strain to the deforming stress is the compliance tensor of the material.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Deformation is the change in the metric properties of a continuous body, meaning that a curve drawn in the initial body placement changes its length when displaced to a curve in the final placement.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] If none of the curves changes length, it is said that a rigid body displacement occurred.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] It is convenient to identify a reference configuration or initial geometric state of the continuum body which all subsequent configurations are referenced from.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] The reference configuration need not be one the body actually will ever occupy.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Often, the configuration at *t* = 0 is considered the reference configuration, *κ*0(**B**).
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] The configuration at the current time t is the *current configuration*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] For deformation analysis, the reference configuration is identified as *undeformed configuration*, and the current configuration as *deformed configuration*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Additionally, time is not considered when analyzing deformation, thus the sequence of configurations between the undeformed and deformed configurations are of no interest.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] The components *X**i* of the position vector **X** of a particle in the reference configuration, taken with respect to the reference coordinate system, are called the *material or reference coordinates*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] There are two methods for analysing the deformation of a continuum.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] One description is made in terms of the material or referential coordinates, called material description or Lagrangian description.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] A second description of deformation is made in terms of the spatial coordinates it is called the spatial description or Eulerian description.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] An **affine deformation** is a deformation that can be completely described by an *affine transformation*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Such a transformation is composed of a linear transformation (such as rotation, shear, extension and compression) and a rigid body translation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Affine deformations are also called **homogeneous deformations**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] A rigid body motion is a special affine deformation that does not involve any shear, extension or compression.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] The transformation matrix **F** is proper orthogonal in order to allow rotations but no reflections.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Deformation implies the change in shape and/or size of the body from an initial or undeformed configuration *κ*0(**B**) to a current or deformed configuration *κt*(**B**) (Figure 1).
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] If after a displacement of the continuum there is a relative displacement between particles, a deformation has occurred.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] On the other hand, if after displacement of the continuum the relative displacement between particles in the current configuration is zero, then there is no deformation and a rigid-body displacement is said to have occurred.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] The vector joining the positions of a particle *P* in the undeformed configuration and deformed configuration is called the displacement vector **u**(**X**,*t*) = *u**i***e***i* in the Lagrangian description, or **U**(**x**,*t*) = *U**J***E***J* in the Eulerian description.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] It is convenient to do the analysis of deformation or motion of a continuum body in terms of the displacement field.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] The partial differentiation of the displacement vector with respect to the material coordinates yields the *material displacement gradient tensor* **∇Xu**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Similarly, the partial differentiation of the displacement vector with respect to the spatial coordinates yields the *spatial displacement gradient tensor* **∇xU**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Homogeneous (or affine) deformations are useful in elucidating the behavior of materials.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Linear or longitudinal deformations of long objects, such as beams and fibers, are called *elongation* or *shortening*; derived quantities are the relative elongation and the stretch ratio.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] Plane deformations are also of interest, particularly in the experimental context.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] A plane deformation, also called *plane strain*, is one where the deformation is restricted to one of the planes in the reference configuration.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] A simple shear deformation is defined as an isochoric plane deformation in which there is a set of line elements with a given reference orientation that do not change length and orientation during the deformation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/deformation-physics] If **e**1 is the fixed reference orientation in which line elements do not deform during the deformation then *λ*1 = 1 and ***F***·**e**1 = **e**1.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The **Navier–Stokes equations** (/nævˈjeɪ ˈstoʊks/ *nav-YAY STOHKS*) describe the motion of viscous fluids.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This system of partial differential equations was named after Claude-Louis Navier and George Gabriel Stokes, who developed them over a few decades of progressive work, from 1822 (Navier) to 1842–1850 (Stokes).
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Siméon Denis Poisson independently achieved the same results.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Navier–Stokes equations mathematically express momentum balance for Newtonian fluids and make use of the conservation of mass.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] They are sometimes accompanied by an equation of state relating pressure, temperature and density.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] They arise from applying Newton's second law to fluid motion, together with the assumption that the stress in the fluid is the sum of a diffusing viscous term (proportional to the gradient of velocity) and a pressure term—hence describing *viscous flow*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Navier–Stokes equations generalize the Euler equations in that the latter model only considers inviscid flow.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Navier–Stokes equations are of great scientific and engineering interest because they may be used to model a wide variety of scenarios.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In their full or simplified forms, they can assist in the design of aircraft and cars, the study of blood flow, the design of power stations, the analysis of pollution, and many other problems.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Coupled with Maxwell's equations, they comprise the fundamentals of magnetohydrodynamics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Navier–Stokes equations are also of great interest in a purely mathematical sense.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Despite their wide range of practical uses, the conjecture that they have smooth (meaning infinitely differentiable) or bounded solutions in three dimensions has not yet been proven.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This is called the Navier–Stokes existence and smoothness problem.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Clay Mathematics Institute has called this one of the seven most important open problems in mathematics and has offered a $1 million prize for a solution or a counterexample.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The solution of the equations is a flow velocity.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] It is a vector field—to every point in a fluid, at any moment in a time interval, it gives a vector whose direction and magnitude are those of the velocity of the fluid at that point in space and at that moment in time.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] It is studied in three spatial dimensions and one time dimension, and higher-dimensional analogues are studied in both pure and applied mathematics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Once the velocity field is calculated, other quantities of interest, such as pressure or temperature, may be found using dynamical equations and relations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This is different from what one normally sees in classical mechanics, where solutions are typically trajectories of the position of a particle or deflection of a continuum.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Studying velocity instead of position makes more sense for a fluid, although for visualization purposes, one can compute various trajectories.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In particular, the streamlines of a vector field, interpreted as flow velocity, are the paths along which a massless fluid particle would travel.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] These paths are the integral curves whose derivative at each point is equal to the vector field, and they can represent visually the behavior of the vector field at a point in time.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In this form, it is apparent that in the assumption of an inviscid fluid – no deviatoric stress – Cauchy equations reduce to the Euler equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] to arrive at the conservation form of the equations of motion.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The left side of the equation describes acceleration, and may be composed of time-dependent and convective components (also the effects of non-inertial coordinates if present).
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The right side of the equation is in effect a summation of hydrostatic effects, the divergence of deviatoric stress and body forces (such as gravity).
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] All non-relativistic balance equations, such as the Navier–Stokes equations, can be derived by beginning with the Cauchy equations and specifying the stress tensor through a constitutive relation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] By expressing the deviatoric (shear) stress tensor in terms of viscosity and the fluid velocity gradient, and assuming constant viscosity, the above Cauchy equations will lead to the Navier–Stokes equations below.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] A significant feature of the Cauchy equation and consequently all other continuum equations (including Euler and Navier–Stokes) is the presence of convective acceleration: the effect of acceleration of a flow with respect to space.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] While individual fluid particles indeed experience time-dependent acceleration, the convective acceleration of the flow field is a spatial effect, one example being fluid speeding up in a nozzle.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Remark: here, the deviatoric stress tensor is denoted ${\textstyle {\boldsymbol {\tau }}}$ as it was in the general continuum equations and in the incompressible flow section.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Both bulk viscosity ${\textstyle \zeta }$ and dynamic viscosity ${\textstyle \mu }$ need not be constant – in general, they depend on two thermodynamics variables if the fluid contains a single chemical species, say for example, pressure and temperature.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Any equation that makes explicit one of these transport coefficient in the conservation variables is called an equation of state.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Apart from its dependence of pressure and temperature, the second viscosity coefficient also depends on the process, that is to say, the second viscosity coefficient is not just a material property.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Example: in the case of a sound wave with a definitive frequency that alternatively compresses and expands a fluid element, the second viscosity coefficient depends on the frequency of the wave.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This dependence is called the *dispersion*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The assumption of setting ${\textstyle \zeta =0}$ is called as the **Stokes hypothesis**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The validity of Stokes hypothesis can be demonstrated for monoatomic gas both experimentally and from the kinetic theory; for other gases and liquids, Stokes hypothesis is generally incorrect.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] If the dynamic $\mu$ and bulk $\zeta$ viscosities are assumed to be uniform in space, the equations in convective form can be simplified further.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] where ${\textstyle {\frac {\mathrm {D} }{\mathrm {D} t}}}$ is the material derivative. ${\textstyle \nu ={\frac {\mu }{\rho }}}$ is the shear kinematic viscosity and ${\textstyle \xi ={\frac {\zeta }{\rho }}}$ is the bulk kinematic viscosity.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The left-hand side changes in the conservation form of the Navier–Stokes momentum equation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The convective acceleration term can also be written as $\mathbf {u} \cdot \nabla \mathbf {u} =(\nabla \times \mathbf {u} )\times \mathbf {u} +{\tfrac {1}{2}}\nabla \mathbf {u} ^{2},$ where the vector ${\textstyle (\nabla \times \mathbf {u} )\times \mathbf {u} }$ is known as the Lamb vector.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] For the special case of an incompressible flow, the pressure constrains the flow so that the volume of fluid elements is constant: isochoric flow resulting in a solenoidal velocity field with ${\textstyle \nabla \cdot \mathbf {u} =0}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This is constitutive equation is also called the **Newtonian law of viscosity**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Dynamic viscosity μ need not be constant – in incompressible flows it can depend on density and on pressure.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Any equation that makes explicit one of these transport coefficient in the conservative variables is called an equation of state.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Incompressibility rules out density and pressure waves like sound or shock waves, so this simplification is not useful if these phenomena are of interest.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] where ${\textstyle \nu ={\frac {\mu }{\rho }}}$ is called the kinematic viscosity.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] where ${\textstyle {\frac {p}{\rho }}}$ is called the unit pressure head.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] which is obtained by taking the divergence of the momentum equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The higher-order term, namely the shear stress divergence ${\textstyle \nabla \cdot {\boldsymbol {\tau }}}$ , has simply reduced to the vector Laplacian term ${\textstyle \mu \nabla ^{2}\mathbf {u} }$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This Laplacian term can be interpreted as the difference between the velocity at a point and the mean velocity in a small surrounding volume.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This implies that – for a Newtonian fluid – viscosity operates as a *diffusion of momentum*, in much the same way as the heat conduction.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In fact neglecting the convection term, incompressible Navier–Stokes equations lead to a vector diffusion equation (namely Stokes equations), but in general the convection term is present, so incompressible Navier–Stokes equations belong to the class of convection–diffusion equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The incompressible Navier–Stokes equations with uniform density and viscosity and conservative external field is the **fundamental equation of hydraulics**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The domain for these equations is commonly a 3 or fewer dimensional Euclidean space, for which an orthogonal coordinate reference frame is usually set to explicit the system of scalar partial differential equations to be solved.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In 3-dimensional orthogonal coordinate systems are 3: Cartesian, cylindrical, and spherical.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] But for the higher order terms (the two coming from the divergence of the deviatoric stress that distinguish Navier–Stokes equations from Euler equations) some tensor calculus is required for deducing an expression in non-cartesian orthogonal coordinate systems.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] A special case of the fundamental equation of hydraulics is the Bernoulli's equation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This result follows from the Helmholtz theorem (also known as the fundamental theorem of vector calculus).
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The first equation is a pressureless governing equation for the velocity, while the second equation for the pressure is a functional of the velocity and is related to the pressure Poisson equation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Thus the governing equation is an integro-differential equation similar to Coulomb's and Biot–Savart's law, not convenient for numerical computation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] for divergence-free test functions ${\textstyle \mathbf {w} }$ satisfying appropriate boundary conditions.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Here, the projections are accomplished by the orthogonality of the solenoidal and irrotational function spaces.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The discrete form of this is eminently suited to finite element computation of divergence-free flow, as we shall see in the next section.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] There, one will be able to address the question, "How does one specify pressure-driven (Poiseuille) problems with a pressureless governing equation?".
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The absence of pressure forces from the governing velocity equation demonstrates that the equation is not a dynamic one, but rather a kinematic equation where the divergence-free condition serves the role of a conservation equation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This would seem to refute the frequent statements that the incompressible pressure enforces the divergence-free condition.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The first equation is the momentum balance equation, while the second represents the mass conservation, namely the continuity equation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] It is desirable to choose basis functions that reflect the essential feature of incompressible flow – the elements must be divergence-free.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] While the velocity is the variable of interest, the existence of the stream function or vector potential is necessary by the Helmholtz theorem.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Further, to determine fluid flow in the absence of a pressure gradient, one can specify the difference of stream function values across a 2D channel, or the line integral of the tangential component of the vector potential around the channel in 3D, the flow being given by Stokes' theorem.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Discussion will be restricted to 2D in the following.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] We further restrict discussion to continuous Hermite finite elements which have at least first-derivative degrees-of-freedom.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] With this, one can draw a large number of candidate triangular and rectangular elements from the plate-bending literature.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] These elements have derivatives as components of the gradient.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Adopting continuous plate-bending elements, interchanging the derivative degrees-of-freedom and changing the sign of the appropriate one gives many families of stream function elements.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Taking the curl of the scalar stream function elements gives divergence-free velocity elements.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The requirement that the stream function elements be continuous assures that the normal component of the velocity is continuous across element interfaces, all that is necessary for vanishing divergence on these interfaces.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Boundary conditions are simple to apply.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The stream function is constant on no-flow surfaces, with no-slip velocity conditions on surfaces.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Stream function differences across open channels determine the flow.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] No boundary conditions are necessary on open boundaries, though consistent values may be used with some problems.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The algebraic equations to be solved are simple to set up, but of course are non-linear, requiring iteration of the linearized equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Similar considerations apply to three-dimensions, but extension from 2D is not immediate because of the vector nature of the potential, and there exists no simple relation between the gradient and the curl as was the case in 2D.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Recovering pressure from the velocity field is easy.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] where the test/weight functions are irrotational.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Any conforming scalar finite element may be used.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] However, the pressure gradient field may also be of interest.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In this case, one can use scalar Hermite elements for the pressure.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] For the test/weight functions ${\textstyle \mathbf {g} _{i}}$ one would choose the irrotational vector elements obtained from the gradient of the pressure element.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The rotating frame of reference introduces some interesting pseudo-forces into the equations through the material derivative term.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Consider a stationary inertial frame of reference ${\textstyle K}$ , and a non-inertial frame of reference ${\textstyle K'}$ , which is translating with velocity ${\textstyle \mathbf {U} (t)}$ and rotating with angular velocity ${\textstyle \Omega (t)}$ with respect to the stationary frame.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Here ${\textstyle \mathbf {x} }$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {u} }$ are measured in the non-inertial frame.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Navier–Stokes equations are strictly a statement of the balance of momentum.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] To fully describe fluid flow, more information is needed, how much depending on the assumptions made.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This additional information may include boundary data (no-slip, capillary surface, etc.), conservation of mass, balance of energy, and/or an equation of state.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Regardless of the flow assumptions, a statement of the conservation of mass is generally necessary.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Therefore, the rate of change of $\rho$ with respect to time ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial \rho }{\partial t}}}$ and the gradient of density ${\textstyle \nabla \rho }$ are equal to zero.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Taking the curl of the incompressible Navier–Stokes equation results in the elimination of pressure.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Differentiating the first with respect to ${\textstyle y}$ , the second with respect to ${\textstyle x}$ and subtracting the resulting equations will eliminate pressure and any conservative force.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] where ${\textstyle \nabla ^{4}}$ is the 2D biharmonic operator and ${\textstyle \nu }$ is the kinematic viscosity, ${\textstyle \nu ={\frac {\mu }{\rho }}}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This single equation together with appropriate boundary conditions describes 2D fluid flow, taking only kinematic viscosity as a parameter.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Note that the equation for creeping flow results when the left side is assumed zero.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] In axisymmetric flow another stream function formulation, called the Stokes stream function, can be used to describe the velocity components of an incompressible flow with one scalar function.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The incompressible Navier–Stokes equation is a differential algebraic equation, having the inconvenient feature that there is no explicit mechanism for advancing the pressure in time.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Consequently, much effort has been expended to eliminate the pressure from all or part of the computational process.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The stream function formulation eliminates the pressure but only in two dimensions and at the expense of introducing higher derivatives and elimination of the velocity, which is the primary variable of interest.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The Navier–Stokes equations are nonlinear partial differential equations in the general case and so remain in almost every real situation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] In some cases, such as one-dimensional flow and Stokes flow (or creeping flow), the equations can be simplified to linear equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The nonlinearity makes most problems difficult or impossible to solve and is the main contributor to the turbulence that the equations model.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The nonlinearity is due to convective acceleration, which is an acceleration associated with the change in velocity over position.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Hence, any convective flow, whether turbulent or not, will involve nonlinearity.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] An example of convective but laminar (nonturbulent) flow would be the passage of a viscous fluid (for example, oil) through a small converging nozzle.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Such flows, whether exactly solvable or not, can often be thoroughly studied and understood.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Turbulence is the time-dependent chaotic behaviour seen in many fluid flows.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] It is generally believed that it is due to the inertia of the fluid as a whole: the culmination of time-dependent and convective acceleration; hence flows where inertial effects are small tend to be laminar (the Reynolds number quantifies how much the flow is affected by inertia).
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] It is believed, though not known with certainty, that the Navier–Stokes equations describe turbulence properly.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Attempts to solve turbulent flow using a laminar solver typically result in a time-unsteady solution, which fails to converge appropriately.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] To counter this, time-averaged equations such as the Reynolds-averaged Navier–Stokes equations (RANS), supplemented with turbulence models, are used in practical computational fluid dynamics (CFD) applications when modeling turbulent flows.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Some models include the Spalart–Allmaras, k–ω, k–ε, and SST models, which add a variety of additional equations to bring closure to the RANS equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Large eddy simulation (LES) can also be used to solve these equations numerically.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This approach is computationally more expensive—in time and in computer memory—than RANS, but produces better results because it explicitly resolves the larger turbulent scales.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Together with supplemental equations (for example, conservation of mass) and well-formulated boundary conditions, the Navier–Stokes equations seem to model fluid motion accurately; even turbulent flows seem (on average) to agree with real world observations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The Navier–Stokes equations assume that the fluid being studied is a continuum (it is infinitely divisible and not composed of particles such as atoms or molecules), and is not moving at relativistic velocities.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] At very small scales or under extreme conditions, real fluids made out of discrete molecules will produce results different from the continuous fluids modeled by the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] For example, capillarity of internal layers in fluids appears for flow with high gradients.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] For large Knudsen number of the problem, the Boltzmann equation may be a suitable replacement.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Failing that, one may have to resort to molecular dynamics or various hybrid methods.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Another limitation is simply the complicated nature of the equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Time-tested formulations exist for common fluid families, but the application of the Navier–Stokes equations to less common families tends to result in very complicated formulations and often to open research problems.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] For this reason, these equations are usually written for Newtonian fluids where the viscosity model is linear; truly general models for the flow of other kinds of fluids (such as blood) do not exist.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The Navier–Stokes equations, even when written explicitly for specific fluids, are rather generic in nature and their proper application to specific problems can be very diverse.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This is partly because there is an enormous variety of problems that may be modeled, ranging from as simple as the distribution of static pressure to as complicated as multiphase flow driven by surface tension.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Generally, application to specific problems begins with some flow assumptions and initial/boundary condition formulation, this may be followed by scale analysis to further simplify the problem.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The boundary condition is the no slip condition.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] From this point onward, more quantities of interest can be easily obtained, such as viscous drag force or net flow rate.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Difficulties may arise when the problem becomes slightly more complicated.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] A seemingly modest twist on the parallel flow above would be the *radial* flow between parallel plates; this involves convection and thus non-linearity.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This ordinary differential equation is what is obtained when the Navier–Stokes equations are written and the flow assumptions applied (additionally, the pressure gradient is solved for).
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The nonlinear term makes this a very difficult problem to solve analytically (a lengthy implicit solution may be found which involves elliptic integrals and roots of cubic polynomials).
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Issues with the actual existence of solutions arise for ${\textstyle R>1.41}$ (approximately; this is not √2), the parameter ${\textstyle R}$ being the Reynolds number with appropriately chosen scales.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This is an example of flow assumptions losing their applicability, and an example of the difficulty in "high" Reynolds number flows.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] A type of natural convection that can be described by the Navier–Stokes equation is the Rayleigh–Bénard convection.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] It is one of the most commonly studied convection phenomena because of its analytical and experimental accessibility.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Some exact solutions to the Navier–Stokes equations exist.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Examples of degenerate cases—with the non-linear terms in the Navier–Stokes equations equal to zero—are Poiseuille flow, Couette flow and the oscillatory Stokes boundary layer.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] But also, more interesting examples, solutions to the full non-linear equations, exist, such as Jeffery–Hamel flow, Von Kármán swirling flow, stagnation point flow, Landau–Squire jet, and Taylor–Green vortex.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Time-dependent self-similar solutions of the three-dimensional non-compressible Navier–Stokes equations in Cartesian coordinate can be given with the help of the Kummer's functions with quadratic arguments.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] For the compressible Navier–Stokes equations the time-dependent self-similar solutions are however the Whittaker functions again with quadratic arguments when the polytropic equation of state is used as a closing condition.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Note that the existence of these exact solutions does not imply they are stable: turbulence may develop at higher Reynolds numbers.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Under additional assumptions, the component parts can be separated.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This solution is valid in the domain *r* ≥ 1 and for *A* < −2*ν*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] There is a singularity at *x* = *y* = *z* = 0.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] A steady-state example with no singularities comes from considering the flow along the lines of a Hopf fibration.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Let ${\textstyle r}$ be a constant radius of the inner coil.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] for arbitrary constants ${\textstyle A}$ and ${\textstyle B}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This is a solution in a non-viscous gas (compressible fluid) whose density, velocities and pressure goes to zero far from the origin.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Two examples of periodic fully-three-dimensional viscous solutions are described in.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] These solutions are defined on a three-dimensional torus $\mathbb {T} ^{3}=[0,L]^{3}$ and are characterized by positive and negative helicity respectively.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The pressure field is obtained from the velocity field as $p=p_{0}-\rho _{0}\|{\boldsymbol {u}}\|^{2}/2$ (where $p_{0}$ and $\rho _{0}$ are reference values for the pressure and density fields respectively).
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Since both the solutions belong to the class of Beltrami flow, the vorticity field is parallel to the velocity and, for the case with positive helicity, is given by $\omega ={\sqrt {3}}\,k\,{\boldsymbol {u}}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] These solutions can be regarded as a generalization in three dimensions of the classic two-dimensional Taylor–Green vortex.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] A 2022 paper provides a less costly, dynamical and recurrent solution of the Navier-Stokes equation for 3D turbulent fluid flows.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] On suitably short time scales, the dynamics of turbulence is deterministic.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Note that gravity has been accounted for as a body force, and the values of ${\textstyle g_{x}}$ , ${\textstyle g_{y}}$ , ${\textstyle g_{z}}$ will depend on the orientation of gravity with respect to the chosen set of coordinates.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] When the flow is incompressible, ${\textstyle \rho }$ does not change for any fluid particle, and its material derivative vanishes: ${\textstyle {\frac {\mathrm {D} \rho }{\mathrm {D} t}}=0}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Thus, for the incompressible version of the Navier–Stokes equation the second part of the viscous terms fall away (see Incompressible flow).
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This system of four equations comprises the most commonly used and studied form.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Though comparatively more compact than other representations, this is still a nonlinear system of partial differential equations for which solutions are difficult to obtain.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This cylindrical representation of the incompressible Navier–Stokes equations is the second most commonly seen (the first being Cartesian above).
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Cylindrical coordinates are chosen to take advantage of symmetry, so that a velocity component can disappear.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] These equations could be (slightly) compacted by, for example, factoring ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{r^{2}}}}$ from the viscous terms.
[src:continuum-mechanics/navier-stokes-equations-p02] However, doing so would undesirably alter the structure of the Laplacian and other quantities.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] In mechanics, **strain** is defined as relative deformation, compared to a *reference* position configuration.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] Different equivalent choices may be made for the expression of a strain field depending on whether it is defined with respect to the initial or the final configuration of the body and on whether the metric tensor or its dual is considered.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] Strain has dimension of a length ratio, with SI base units of meter per meter (m/m).
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] Hence strains are dimensionless and are usually expressed as a decimal fraction or a percentage.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] Parts-per notation is also used, e.g., parts per million or parts per billion (sometimes called "microstrains" and "nanostrains", respectively), corresponding to μm/m and nm/m.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] Strain can be formulated as the spatial derivative of displacement: ${\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}\doteq {\cfrac {\partial }{\partial \mathbf {X} }}\left(\mathbf {x} -\mathbf {X} \right)={\boldsymbol {F}}'-{\boldsymbol {I}},$ where **I** is the identity tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The spatial derivative of a uniform translation is zero, thus strains measure how much a given displacement differs locally from a rigid-body motion.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] A strain is in general a tensor quantity.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] Physical insight into strains can be gained by observing that a given strain can be decomposed into normal and shear components.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The amount of stretch or compression along material line elements or fibers is the *normal strain*, and the amount of distortion associated with the sliding of plane layers over each other is the *shear strain*, within a deforming body.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] This could be applied by elongation, shortening, or volume changes, or angular distortion.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] However, it is sufficient to know the normal and shear components of strain on a set of three mutually perpendicular directions.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] If there is an increase in length of the material line, the normal strain is called *tensile strain*; otherwise, if there is reduction or compression in the length of the material line, it is called *compressive strain*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] In each of these theories the strain is then defined differently.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The *engineering strain* is the most common definition applied to materials used in mechanical and structural engineering, which are subjected to very small deformations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The *true shear strain* is defined as the change in the angle (in radians) between two material line elements initially perpendicular to each other in the undeformed or initial configuration.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The *engineering shear strain* is defined as the tangent of that angle, and is equal to the length of deformation at its maximum divided by the perpendicular length in the plane of force application, which sometimes makes it easier to calculate.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The **stretch ratio** or **extension ratio** (symbol λ) is an alternative measure related to the extensional or normal strain of an axially loaded differential line element.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The extension ratio λ is related to the engineering strain *e* by $e=\lambda -1$ This equation implies that when the normal strain is zero, so that there is no deformation, the stretch ratio is equal to unity.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The stretch ratio is used in the analysis of materials that exhibit large deformations, such as elastomers, which can sustain stretch ratios of 3 or 4 before they fail.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] On the other hand, traditional engineering materials, such as concrete or steel, fail at much lower stretch ratios.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The **logarithmic strain** ε, also called, *true strain* or *Hencky strain*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The logarithmic strain provides the correct measure of the final strain when deformation takes place in a series of increments, taking into account the influence of the strain path.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The (infinitesimal) **strain tensor** (symbol ${\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}$ ) is defined in the International System of Quantities (ISQ), more specifically in ISO 80000-4 (Mechanics), as a "tensor quantity representing the deformation of matter caused by stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] Thus, strains are classified as either *normal* or *shear*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] A *normal strain* is perpendicular to the face of an element, and a *shear strain* is parallel to it.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] These definitions are consistent with those of normal stress and shear stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] Consider a two-dimensional, infinitesimal, rectangular material element with dimensions *dx* × *dy*, which, after deformation, takes the form of a rhombus.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The deformation is described by the displacement field **u**.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] For an isotropic material that obeys Hooke's law, a normal stress will cause a normal strain.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] The engineering shear strain (*γxy*) is defined as the change in angle between lines *AC* and *AB*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] In case of pure shear, we can see that there is no change of the volume.
[src:continuum-mechanics/strain-mechanics] A strain field associated with a displacement is defined, at any point, by the change in length of the tangent vectors representing the speeds of arbitrarily parametrized curves passing through that point.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In continuum mechanics, **stress** is a physical quantity that describes forces present during deformation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] For example, an object being pulled apart, such as a stretched elastic band, is subject to *tensile* stress and may undergo elongation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] An object being pushed together, such as a crumpled sponge, is subject to *compressive* stress and may undergo shortening.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The greater the force and the smaller the cross-sectional area of the body on which it acts, the greater the stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress has dimension of force per area, with SI units of newtons per square meter (N/m2) or pascal (Pa).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress expresses the internal forces that neighbouring particles of a continuous material exert on each other, while *strain* is the measure of the relative deformation of the material.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] For example, when a solid vertical bar is supporting an overhead weight, each particle in the bar pushes on the particles immediately below it.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] When a liquid is in a closed container under pressure, each particle gets pushed against by all the surrounding particles.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The container walls and the pressure-inducing surface (such as a piston) push against them in (Newtonian) reaction.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] These macroscopic forces are actually the net result of a very large number of intermolecular forces and collisions between the particles in those molecules.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress is frequently represented by a lowercase Greek letter sigma (*σ*).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Strain inside a material may arise by various mechanisms, such as *stress* as applied by external forces to the bulk material (like gravity) or to its surface (like contact forces, external pressure, or friction).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Any strain (deformation) of a solid material generates an internal *elastic stress*, analogous to the reaction force of a spring, that tends to restore the material to its original non-deformed state.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In liquids and gases, only deformations that change the volume generate persistent elastic stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] If the deformation changes gradually with time, even in fluids there will usually be some *viscous stress*, opposing that change.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Elastic and viscous stresses are usually combined under the name *mechanical stress*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Significant stress may exist even when deformation is negligible or non-existent (a common assumption when modeling the flow of water).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress may exist in the absence of external forces; such *built-in stress* is important, for example, in prestressed concrete and tempered glass.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress may also be imposed on a material without the application of net forces, for example by changes in temperature or chemical composition, or by external electromagnetic fields (as in piezoelectric and magnetostrictive materials).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The relation between mechanical stress, strain, and the strain rate can be quite complicated, although a linear approximation may be adequate in practice if the quantities are sufficiently small.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress that exceeds certain strength limits of the material will result in permanent deformation (such as plastic flow, fracture, cavitation) or even change its crystal structure and chemical composition.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Humans have known about stress inside materials since ancient times.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Until the 17th century, this understanding was largely intuitive and empirical, though this did not prevent the development of relatively advanced technologies like the composite bow and glass blowing.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] With those tools, Augustin-Louis Cauchy was able to give the first rigorous and general mathematical model of a deformed elastic body by introducing the notions of stress and strain.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Cauchy observed that the force across an imaginary surface was a linear function of its normal vector; and, moreover, that it must be a symmetric function (with zero total momentum).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The understanding of stress in liquids started with Newton, who provided a differential formula for friction forces (shear stress) in parallel laminar flow.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress is defined as the force across a small boundary per unit area of that boundary, for all orientations of the boundary.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Derived from a physical quantity (force) and a purely geometrical quantity (area), stress is also a physical quantity, like velocity, torque or energy, that can be quantified and analyzed without explicit consideration of the nature of the material or of its physical causes.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Following the basic premises of continuum mechanics, stress is a macroscopic concept.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Namely, the particles considered in its definition and analysis should be just small enough to be treated as homogeneous in composition and state, but still large enough to ignore quantum effects and the detailed motions of molecules.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Depending on the context, one may also assume that the particles are large enough to allow the averaging out of other microscopic features, like the grains of a metal rod or the fibers of a piece of wood.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Quantitatively, the stress is expressed by the *Cauchy traction vector* *T* defined as the traction force *F* between adjacent parts of the material across an imaginary separating surface *S*, divided by the area of *S*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In a fluid at rest the force is perpendicular to the surface, and is the familiar pressure.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In a solid, or in a flow of viscous liquid, the force *F* may not be perpendicular to *S*; hence the stress across a surface must be regarded a vector quantity, not a scalar.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Moreover, the direction and magnitude generally depend on the orientation of *S*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Thus the stress state of the material must be described by a tensor, called the (Cauchy) stress tensor; which is a linear function that relates the normal vector *n* of a surface *S* to the traction vector *T* across *S*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] With respect to any chosen coordinate system, the Cauchy stress tensor can be represented as a symmetric matrix of 3×3 real numbers.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Even within a homogeneous body, the stress tensor may vary from place to place, and may change over time; therefore, the stress within a material is, in general, a time-varying tensor field.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In general, the stress *T* that a particle *P* applies on another particle *Q* across a surface *S* can have any direction relative to *S*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The vector *T* may be regarded as the sum of two components: the *normal stress* (compression or tension) perpendicular to the surface, and the *shear stress* that is parallel to the surface.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] If the normal unit vector *n* of the surface (pointing from *Q* towards *P*) is assumed fixed, the normal component can be expressed by a single number, the dot product *T* · *n*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] This number will be positive if *P* is "pulling" on *Q* (tensile stress), and negative if *P* is "pushing" against *Q* (compressive stress).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The shear component is then the vector *T* − (*T* · *n*)*n*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The dimension of stress is that of pressure, and therefore its coordinates are measured in the same units as pressure: namely, pascals (Pa, that is, newtons per square metre) in the International System, or pounds per square inch (psi) in the Imperial system.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Because mechanical stresses easily exceed a million Pascals, MPa, which stands for megapascal, is a common unit of stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress in a material body may be due to multiple physical causes, including external influences and internal physical processes.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Some of these agents (like gravity, changes in temperature and phase, and electromagnetic fields) act on the bulk of the material, varying continuously with position and time.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Other agents (like external loads and friction, ambient pressure, and contact forces) may create stresses and forces that are concentrated on certain surfaces, lines or points; and possibly also on very short time intervals (as in the impulses due to collisions).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In active matter, self-propulsion of microscopic particles generates macroscopic stress profiles.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In general, the stress distribution in a body is expressed as a piecewise continuous function of space and time.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Conversely, stress is usually correlated with various effects on the material, possibly including changes in physical properties like birefringence, polarization, and permeability.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The imposition of stress by an external agent usually creates some strain (deformation) in the material, even if it is too small to be detected.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In a solid material, such strain will in turn generate an internal elastic stress, analogous to the reaction force of a stretched spring, tending to restore the material to its original undeformed state.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Fluid materials (liquids, gases and plasmas) by definition can only oppose deformations that would change their volume.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] If the deformation changes with time, even in fluids there will usually be some viscous stress, opposing that change.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Such stresses can be either shear or normal in nature.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Molecular origin of shear stresses in fluids is given in the article on viscosity.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The same for normal viscous stresses can be found in Sharma (2019).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The relation between stress and its effects and causes, including deformation and rate of change of deformation, can be quite complicated (although a linear approximation may be adequate in practice if the quantities are small enough).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In some situations, the stress within a body may adequately be described by a single number, or by a single vector (a number and a direction).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Three such **simple stress** situations, that are often encountered in engineering design, are the *uniaxial normal stress*, the *simple shear stress*, and the *isotropic normal stress*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] A common situation with a simple stress pattern is when a straight rod, with uniform material and cross section, is subjected to tension by opposite forces of magnitude F along its axis.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] If the system is in equilibrium and not changing with time, and the weight of the bar can be neglected, then through each transversal section of the bar the top part must pull on the bottom part with the same force, *F* with continuity through the full cross-sectional area*, A*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] This type of stress may be called (simple) normal stress or uniaxial stress; specifically, (uniaxial, simple, etc.) tensile stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] If the load is compression on the bar, rather than stretching it, the analysis is the same except that the force *F* and the stress $\sigma$ change sign, and the stress is called compressive stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] This analysis assumes the stress is evenly distributed over the entire cross-section.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In practice, depending on how the bar is attached at the ends and how it was manufactured, this assumption may not be valid.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In that case, the value $\sigma$ = *F*/*A* will be only the average stress, called *engineering stress* or *nominal stress*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] If the bar's length *L* is many times its diameter *D*, and it has no gross defects or built-in stress, then the stress can be assumed to be uniformly distributed over any cross-section that is more than a few times *D* from both ends.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] (This observation is known as the Saint-Venant's principle).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Normal stress occurs in many other situations besides axial tension and compression.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Another variant of normal stress is the *hoop stress* that occurs on the walls of a cylindrical pipe or vessel filled with pressurized fluid.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Let *F* be the magnitude of those forces, and *M* be the midplane of that layer.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Just as in the normal stress case, the part of the layer on one side of *M* must pull the other part with the same force *F*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] For any plane *S* that is perpendicular to the layer, the net internal force across *S*, and hence the stress, will be zero.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] As in the case of an axially loaded bar, in practice the shear stress may not be uniformly distributed over the layer; so, as before, the ratio *F*/*A* will only be an average ("nominal", "engineering") stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] That average is often sufficient for practical purposes.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Shear stress is observed also when a cylindrical bar such as a shaft is subjected to opposite torques at its ends.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In that case, the shear stress on each cross-section is parallel to the cross-section, but oriented tangentially relative to the axis, and increases with distance from the axis.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Significant shear stress occurs in the middle plate (the "web") of I-beams under bending loads, due to the web constraining the end plates ("flanges").
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Another simple type of stress occurs when the material body is under equal compression or tension in all directions.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In these situations, the stress across any imaginary internal surface turns out to be equal in magnitude and always directed perpendicularly to the surface independently of the surface's orientation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] This type of stress may be called *isotropic normal* or just *isotropic*; if it is compressive, it is called *hydrostatic pressure* or just *pressure*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Gases by definition cannot withstand tensile stresses, but some liquids may withstand very large amounts of isotropic tensile stress under some circumstances. see Z-tube.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Parts with rotational symmetry, such as wheels, axles, pipes, and pillars, are very common in engineering.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Often the stress patterns that occur in such parts have rotational or even cylindrical symmetry.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The analysis of such cylinder stresses can take advantage of the symmetry to reduce the dimension of the domain and/or of the stress tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Often, mechanical bodies experience more than one type of stress at the same time; this is called *combined stress*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In normal and shear stress, the magnitude of the stress is maximum for surfaces that are perpendicular to a certain direction d , and zero across any surfaces that are parallel to d .
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] When the shear stress is zero only across surfaces that are perpendicular to one particular direction, the stress is called *biaxial*, and can be viewed as the sum of two normal or shear stresses.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In the most general case, called *triaxial stress*, the stress is nonzero across every surface element.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Combined stresses cannot be described by a single vector.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Even if the material is stressed in the same way throughout the volume of the body, the stress across any theoretical surface will depend on the orientation of that surface, in a non-trivial way.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Cauchy observed that the stress vector T across a surface will always be a linear function of the surface's normal vector n , the unit-length vector that is perpendicular to it.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] That is, $T={\boldsymbol {\sigma }}(n)$ , where the function ${\boldsymbol {\sigma }}$ satisfies ${\boldsymbol {\sigma }}(\alpha u+\beta v)=\alpha {\boldsymbol {\sigma }}(u)+\beta {\boldsymbol {\sigma }}(v)$ for any vectors $u,v$ and any real numbers $\alpha ,\beta$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The function ${\boldsymbol {\sigma }}$ , now called the (Cauchy) stress tensor, completely describes the stress state of a uniformly stressed body.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Like any linear map between vectors, the stress tensor can be represented in any chosen Cartesian coordinate system by a 3×3 matrix of real numbers.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The linear relation between T and n follows from the fundamental laws of conservation of linear momentum and static equilibrium of forces, and is therefore mathematically exact, for any material and any stress situation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The components of the Cauchy stress tensor at every point in a material satisfy the equilibrium equations (Cauchy's equations of motion for zero acceleration).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Moreover, the principle of conservation of angular momentum implies that the stress tensor is symmetric, that is $\sigma _{12}=\sigma _{21}$ , $\sigma _{13}=\sigma _{31}$ , and $\sigma _{23}=\sigma _{32}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Therefore, the stress state of the medium at any point and instant can be specified by only six independent parameters, rather than nine.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] A graphical representation of this transformation law is the Mohr's circle of stress distribution.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] As a symmetric 3×3 real matrix, the stress tensor ${\boldsymbol {\sigma }}$ has three mutually orthogonal unit-length eigenvectors $e_{1},e_{2},e_{3}$ and three real eigenvalues $\lambda _{1},\lambda _{2},\lambda _{3}$ , such that ${\boldsymbol {\sigma }}e_{i}=\lambda _{i}e_{i}$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Therefore, in a coordinate system with axes $e_{1},e_{2},e_{3}$ , the stress tensor is a diagonal matrix, and has only the three normal components $\lambda _{1},\lambda _{2},\lambda _{3}$ the principal stresses.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] If the three eigenvalues are equal, the stress is an isotropic compression or tension, always perpendicular to any surface, there is no shear stress, and the tensor is a diagonal matrix in any coordinate frame.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In general, stress is not uniformly distributed over a material body, and may vary with time.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Therefore, the stress tensor must be defined for each point and each moment, by considering an infinitesimal particle of the medium surrounding that point, and taking the average stresses in that particle as being the stresses at the point.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Human-made objects are often made from stock plates of various materials by operations that do not change their essentially two-dimensional character, like cutting, drilling, gentle bending and welding along the edges.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The description of stress in such bodies can be simplified by modeling those parts as two-dimensional surfaces rather than three-dimensional bodies.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In that view, one redefines a "particle" as being an infinitesimal patch of the plate's surface, so that the boundary between adjacent particles becomes an infinitesimal line element; both are implicitly extended in the third dimension, normal to (straight through) the plate.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] "Stress" is then redefined as being a measure of the internal forces between two adjacent "particles" across their common line element, divided by the length of that line.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Some components of the stress tensor can be ignored, but since particles are not infinitesimal in the third dimension one can no longer ignore the torque that a particle applies on its neighbors.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] That torque is modeled as a *bending stress* that tends to change the curvature of the plate.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] These simplifications may not hold at welds, at sharp bends and creases (where the radius of curvature is comparable to the thickness of the plate).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The analysis of stress can be considerably simplified also for thin bars, beams or wires of uniform (or smoothly varying) composition and cross-section that are subjected to moderate bending and twisting.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] For those bodies, one may consider only cross-sections that are perpendicular to the bar's axis, and redefine a "particle" as being a piece of wire with infinitesimal length between two such cross sections.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress analysis is a branch of applied physics that covers the determination of the internal distribution of internal forces in solid objects.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] It is an essential tool in engineering for the study and design of structures such as tunnels, dams, mechanical parts, and structural frames, under prescribed or expected loads.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] It is also important in many other disciplines; for example, in geology, to study phenomena like plate tectonics, vulcanism and avalanches; and in biology, to understand the anatomy of living beings.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress analysis is generally concerned with objects and structures that can be assumed to be in macroscopic static equilibrium.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] By Newton's laws of motion, any external forces being applied to such a system must be balanced by internal reaction forces, which are almost always surface contact forces between adjacent particles — that is, as stress.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Since every particle needs to be in equilibrium, this reaction stress will generally propagate from particle to particle, creating a stress distribution throughout the body.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The typical problem in stress analysis is to determine these internal stresses, given the external forces that are acting on the system.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In stress analysis one normally disregards the physical causes of the forces or the precise nature of the materials.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Instead, one assumes that the stresses are related to deformation (and, in non-static problems, to the rate of deformation) of the material by known constitutive equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress analysis may be carried out experimentally, by applying loads to the actual artifact or to scale model, and measuring the resulting stresses, by any of several available methods.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] This approach is often used for safety certification and monitoring.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Most stress is analysed by mathematical methods, especially during design.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The basic stress analysis problem can be formulated by Euler's equations of motion for continuous bodies (which are consequences of Newton's laws for conservation of linear momentum and angular momentum) and the Euler-Cauchy stress principle, together with the appropriate constitutive equations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Thus one obtains a system of partial differential equations involving the stress tensor field and the strain tensor field, as unknown functions to be determined.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The external body forces appear as the independent ("right-hand side") term in the differential equations, while the concentrated forces appear as boundary conditions.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] The basic stress analysis problem is therefore a boundary-value problem.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress analysis for elastic structures is based on the theory of elasticity and infinitesimal strain theory.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] When the applied loads cause permanent deformation, one must use more complicated constitutive equations, that can account for the physical processes involved (plastic flow, fracture, phase change, etc.).
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Engineered structures are usually designed so the maximum expected stresses are well within the range of linear elasticity (the generalization of Hooke's law for continuous media); that is, the deformations caused by internal stresses are linearly related to them.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In this case the differential equations that define the stress tensor are linear, and the problem becomes much easier.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] For one thing, the stress at any point will be a linear function of the loads, too.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] For small enough stresses, even non-linear systems can usually be assumed to be linear.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Stress analysis is simplified when the physical dimensions and the distribution of loads allow the structure to be treated as one- or two-dimensional.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In the analysis of trusses, for example, the stress field may be assumed to be uniform and uniaxial over each member.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Then the differential equations reduce to a finite set of equations (usually linear) with finitely many unknowns.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] In other contexts one may be able to reduce the three-dimensional problem to a two-dimensional one, and/or replace the general stress and strain tensors by simpler models like uniaxial tension/compression, simple shear, etc.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Still, for two- or three-dimensional cases one must solve a partial differential equation problem.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Analytical or closed-form solutions to the differential equations can be obtained when the geometry, constitutive relations, and boundary conditions are simple enough.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Otherwise one must generally resort to numerical approximations such as the finite element method, the finite difference method, and the boundary element method.
[src:continuum-mechanics/stress-mechanics] Other useful stress measures include the first and second Piola–Kirchhoff stress tensors, the Biot stress tensor, and the Kirchhoff stress tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In mathematics, a **tensor** is an algebraic object that describes a multilinear relationship between sets of algebraic objects associated with a vector space.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Tensors may map between different objects such as vectors, scalars, and even other tensors.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] There are many types of tensors, including scalars and vectors (which are the simplest tensors), dual vectors, multilinear maps between vector spaces, and even some operations such as the dot product.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Tensors are defined independent of any basis, although they are often referred to by their components in a basis related to a particular coordinate system; those components form an array, which can be thought of as a high-dimensional matrix.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In applications, it is common to study situations in which a different tensor can occur at each point of an object.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For example, the stress within an object may vary from one location to another.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A family of tensors, that vary across space in this way, is a tensor field.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In some areas, tensor fields are so ubiquitous that they are often simply called "tensors".
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Tullio Levi-Civita and Gregorio Ricci-Curbastro popularised tensors in 1900 – continuing the earlier work of Bernhard Riemann, Elwin Bruno Christoffel, and others – as part of the *absolute differential calculus*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The concept enabled an alternative formulation of the intrinsic differential geometry of a manifold in the form of the Riemann curvature tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Although seemingly different, the various approaches to defining tensors describe the same geometric concept using different language and at different levels of abstraction.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A tensor may be represented as a (potentially multidimensional) array.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Just as a vector in an n-dimensional space is represented by a one-dimensional array with n components with respect to a given basis, any tensor with respect to a basis is represented by a multidimensional array.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For example, a linear operator is represented in a basis as a two-dimensional square *n* × *n* array.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The numbers in the multidimensional array are known as the *components* or *elements* of the tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] They are denoted by indices giving their position in the array, as subscripts and superscripts, following the symbolic name of the tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For example, the components of an order-2 tensor T could be denoted *T**ij* , where i and j are indices running from 1 to n, or also by *T* *i* *j*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Whether an index is displayed as a superscript or subscript depends on the transformation properties of the tensor, described below.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Thus while *T**ij* and *T* *i* *j* can both be expressed as *n*-by-*n* matrices, and are numerically related via index juggling, the difference in their transformation laws indicates it would be improper to add them together.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The total number of indices (m) required to identify each component uniquely is equal to the *dimension* or the number of *ways* of an array, which is why a tensor is sometimes referred to as an m-dimensional array or an m-way array.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The total number of indices is also called the *order*, *degree* or *rank* of a tensor, although the term "rank" generally has another meaning in the context of matrices and tensors.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Just as the components of a vector change when we change the basis of the vector space, the components of a tensor also change under such a transformation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Each type of tensor comes equipped with a *transformation law* that details how the components of the tensor respond to a change of basis.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Here *R**j**i* are the entries of the change of basis matrix, and in the rightmost expression the summation sign was suppressed: this is the Einstein summation convention, which will be used throughout this article.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] where the hat denotes the components in the new basis.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This is called a *contravariant* transformation law, because the vector components transform by the *inverse* of the change of basis.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This is called a *covariant* transformation law, because the covector components transform by the *same matrix* as the change of basis matrix.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The components of a more general tensor are transformed by some combination of covariant and contravariant transformations, with one transformation law for each index.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] If the transformation matrix of an index is the inverse matrix of the basis transformation, then the index is called *contravariant* and is conventionally denoted with an upper index (superscript).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] If the transformation matrix of an index is the basis transformation itself, then the index is called *covariant* and is denoted with a lower index (subscript).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] As a simple example, the matrix of a linear operator with respect to a basis is a rectangular array T that transforms under a change of basis matrix $R=\left(R_{i}^{j}\right)$ by ${\hat {T}}=R^{-1}TR$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For the individual matrix entries, this transformation law has the form ${\hat {T}}_{j'}^{i'}=\left(R^{-1}\right)_{i}^{i'}T_{j}^{i}R_{j'}^{j}$ so the tensor corresponding to the matrix of a linear operator has one covariant and one contravariant index: it is of type (1,1).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Combinations of covariant and contravariant components with the same index allow us to express geometric invariants.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] where $\delta _{j}^{k}$ is the Kronecker delta, which functions similarly to the identity matrix, and has the effect of renaming indices (*j* into *k* in this example).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Similarly, a linear operator, viewed as a geometric object, does not actually depend on a basis: it is just a linear map that accepts a vector as an argument and produces another vector.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Here the primed indices denote components in the new coordinates, and the unprimed indices denote the components in the old coordinates.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Such a tensor is said to be of order or *type* (*p*, *q*).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The terms "order", "type", "rank", "valence", and "degree" are all sometimes used for the same concept.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Here, the term "order" or "total order" will be used for the total dimension of the array (or its generalization in other definitions), *p* + *q* in the preceding example, and the term "type" for the pair giving the number of contravariant and covariant indices.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A tensor of type (*p*, *q*) is also called a (*p*, *q*)-tensor for short.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The definition of a tensor as a multidimensional array satisfying a transformation law traces back to the work of Ricci.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] An equivalent definition of a tensor uses the representations of the general linear group.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] There is an action of the general linear group on the set of all ordered bases of an *n*-dimensional vector space.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Let *F* be the set of all ordered bases.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Then *F* is a principal homogeneous space for GL(*n*).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Let *W* be a vector space and let $\rho$ be a representation of GL(*n*) on *W* (that is, a group homomorphism $\rho :{\text{GL}}(n)\to {\text{GL}}(W)$ ).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Then a tensor of type $\rho$ is an equivariant map $T:F\to W$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] When $\rho$ is a tensor representation of the general linear group, this gives the usual definition of tensors as multidimensional arrays.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This definition is often used to describe tensors on manifolds, and readily generalizes to other groups.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A downside to the definition of a tensor using the multidimensional array approach is that it is not apparent from the definition that the defined object is indeed basis independent, as is expected from an intrinsically geometric object.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Although it is possible to show that transformation laws indeed ensure independence from the basis, sometimes a more intrinsic definition is preferred.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] One approach that is common in differential geometry is to define tensors relative to a fixed (finite-dimensional) vector space *V*, which is usually taken to be a particular vector space of some geometrical significance like the tangent space to a manifold.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] where *V*∗ is the corresponding dual space of covectors, which is linear in each of its arguments.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The above assumes *V* is a vector space over the real numbers, ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] More generally, *V* can be taken over any field *F* (e.g. the complex numbers), with *F* replacing ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ as the codomain of the multilinear maps.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] a (*p* + *q*)-dimensional array of components can be obtained.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A different choice of basis will yield different components.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] But, because *T* is linear in all of its arguments, the components satisfy the tensor transformation law used in the multilinear array definition.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The multidimensional array of components of *T* thus form a tensor according to that definition.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Moreover, such an array can be realized as the components of some multilinear map *T*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This motivates viewing multilinear maps as the intrinsic objects underlying tensors.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In viewing a tensor as a multilinear map, it is conventional to identify the double dual *V*∗∗ of the vector space *V*, i.e., the space of linear functionals on the dual vector space *V*∗, with the vector space *V*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] There is always a natural linear map from *V* to its double dual, given by evaluating a linear form in *V*∗ against a vector in *V*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This linear mapping is an isomorphism in finite dimensions, and it is often then expedient to identify *V* with its double dual.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For some mathematical applications, a more abstract approach is sometimes useful.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This can be achieved by defining tensors in terms of elements of tensor products of vector spaces, which in turn are defined through a universal property as explained here and here.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A basis *v**i* of *V* and basis *w**j* of *W* naturally induce a basis *v**i* ⊗ *w**j* of the tensor product *V* ⊗ *W*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The components of a tensor *T* are the coefficients of the tensor with respect to the basis obtained from a basis {**e***i*} for *V* and its dual basis {***ε****j*}, i.e.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Using the properties of the tensor product, it can be shown that these components satisfy the transformation law for a type (*p*, *q*) tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Moreover, the universal property of the tensor product gives a one-to-one correspondence between tensors defined in this way and tensors defined as multilinear maps.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The last line is using the universal property of the tensor product, that there is a 1 to 1 correspondence between maps from $\operatorname {Hom} ^{2}\left(U^{*}\times V^{*};\mathbb {F} \right)$ and $\operatorname {Hom} \left(U^{*}\otimes V^{*};\mathbb {F} \right)$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Tensor products can be defined in great generality – for example, involving arbitrary modules over a ring.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In principle, one could define a "tensor" simply to be an element of any tensor product.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] However, the mathematics literature usually reserves the term *tensor* for an element of a tensor product of any number of copies of a single vector space *V* and its dual, as above.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This discussion of tensors so far assumes finite dimensionality of the spaces involved, where the spaces of tensors obtained by each of these constructions are naturally isomorphic.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Constructions of spaces of tensors based on the tensor product and multilinear mappings can be generalized, essentially without modification, to vector bundles or coherent sheaves.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For infinite-dimensional vector spaces, inequivalent topologies lead to inequivalent notions of tensor, and these various isomorphisms may or may not hold depending on what exactly is meant by a tensor (see topological tensor product).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In some applications, it is the tensor product of Hilbert spaces that is intended, whose properties are the most similar to the finite-dimensional case.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A more modern view is that it is the tensors' structure as a symmetric monoidal category that encodes their most important properties, rather than the specific models of those categories.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In many applications, especially in differential geometry and physics, it is natural to consider a tensor with components that are functions of the point in a space.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This was the setting of Ricci's original work.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In modern mathematical terminology such an object is called a tensor field, often referred to simply as a tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In this context, a coordinate basis is often chosen for the tangent vector space.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The concepts of later tensor analysis arose from the work of Carl Friedrich Gauss in differential geometry, and the formulation was much influenced by the theory of algebraic forms and invariants developed during the middle of the nineteenth century.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The word "tensor" itself was introduced in 1846 by William Rowan Hamilton to describe something different from what is now meant by a tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Gibbs introduced dyadics and polyadic algebra, which are also tensors in the modern sense.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The contemporary usage was introduced by Woldemar Voigt in 1898.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Tensor calculus was developed around 1890 by Gregorio Ricci-Curbastro under the title *absolute differential calculus*, and originally presented in 1892.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] It was made accessible to many mathematicians by the publication of Ricci-Curbastro and Tullio Levi-Civita's 1900 classic text *Méthodes de calcul différentiel absolu et leurs applications* (Methods of absolute differential calculus and their applications).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In Ricci's notation, he refers to "systems" with covariant and contravariant components, which are known as tensor fields in the modern sense.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In the 20th century, the subject came to be known as *tensor analysis*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] It achieved broader acceptance beginning with Hermann Minkowski's application to special relativity in 1908 and his development of the concept of spacetime.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Albert Einstein learned about them, with great difficulty, from the geometer Marcel Grossmann.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Levi-Civita then initiated a correspondence with Einstein to correct mistakes Einstein had made in his use of tensor analysis.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Einstein's general relativity was formulated in the language of tensors.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Tensors and tensor fields were also found to be useful in other fields such as continuum mechanics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Some well-known examples of tensors in differential geometry are quadratic forms such as metric tensors, and the Riemann curvature tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The exterior algebra of Hermann Grassmann, from the middle of the nineteenth century, is itself a tensor theory, and highly geometric, but it was some time before it was seen, with the theory of differential forms, as naturally unified with tensor calculus.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The work of Élie Cartan made differential forms one of the basic kinds of tensors used in mathematics, and Hassler Whitney popularized the tensor product.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] From about the 1920s onwards, it was realised that tensors play a basic role in algebraic topology (for example in the Künneth theorem).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Correspondingly there are types of tensors at work in many branches of abstract algebra, particularly in homological algebra and representation theory.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Multilinear algebra can be developed in greater generality than for scalars coming from a field.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For example, scalars can come from a ring.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] But the theory is then less geometric and computations more technical and less algorithmic.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Tensors are generalized within category theory by means of the concept of monoidal category, from the 1960s.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] An elementary example of a mapping describable as a tensor is the dot product, which maps two vectors to a scalar.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The cross product, where two vectors are mapped to a third one, is strictly speaking not a tensor because it changes its sign under those transformations that change the orientation of the coordinate system.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The totally anti-symmetric symbol $\varepsilon _{ijk}$ nevertheless allows a convenient handling of the cross product in equally oriented three dimensional coordinate systems.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This table shows important examples of tensors on vector spaces and tensor fields on manifolds.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The tensors are classified according to their type (*n*, *m*), where *n* is the number of contravariant indices, *m* is the number of covariant indices, and *n* + *m* gives the total order of the tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For example, a bilinear form is the same thing as a (0, 2)-tensor; an inner product is an example of a (0, 2)-tensor, but not all (0, 2)-tensors are inner products.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In the (0, *M*)-entry of the table, *M* denotes the dimensionality of the underlying vector space or manifold because for each dimension of the space, a separate index is needed to select that dimension to get a maximally covariant antisymmetric tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Raising an index on an (*n*, *m*)-tensor produces an (*n* + 1, *m* − 1)-tensor; this corresponds to moving diagonally down and to the left on the table.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Symmetrically, lowering an index corresponds to moving diagonally up and to the right on the table.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Contraction of an upper with a lower index of an (*n*, *m*)-tensor produces an (*n* − 1, *m* − 1)-tensor; this corresponds to moving diagonally up and to the left on the table.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Orientation defined by an ordered set of vectors.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Reversed orientation corresponds to negating the exterior product.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] (signed point), 1 (directed line segment, or vector), 2 (oriented plane element), 3 (oriented volume).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Assuming a basis of a real vector space, e.g., a coordinate frame in the ambient space, a tensor can be represented as an organized multidimensional array of numerical values with respect to this specific basis.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Changing the basis transforms the values in the array in a characteristic way that allows to *define* tensors as objects adhering to this transformational behavior.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For example, there are invariants of tensors that must be preserved under any change of the basis, thereby making only certain multidimensional arrays of numbers a tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Compare this to the array representing $\varepsilon _{ijk}$ not being a tensor, for the sign change under transformations changing the orientation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Because the components of vectors and their duals transform differently under the change of their dual bases, there is a covariant and/or contravariant transformation law that relates the arrays, which represent the tensor with respect to one basis and that with respect to the other one.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The numbers of, respectively, vectors: n (contravariant indices) and dual vectors: m (covariant indices) in the input and output of a tensor determine the *type* (or *valence*) of the tensor, a pair of natural numbers (*n*, *m*), which determine the precise form of the transformation law.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The *order* of a tensor is the sum of these two numbers.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The order (also *degree* or *rank*) of a tensor is thus the sum of the orders of its arguments plus the order of the resulting tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This is also the dimensionality of the array of numbers needed to represent the tensor with respect to a specific basis, or equivalently, the number of indices needed to label each component in that array.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For example, in a fixed basis, a standard linear map that maps a vector to a vector, is represented by a matrix (a 2-dimensional array), and therefore is a 2nd-order tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A simple vector can be represented as a 1-dimensional array, and is therefore a 1st-order tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Scalars are simple numbers and are thus 0th-order tensors.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This way the tensor representing the scalar product, taking two vectors and resulting in a scalar has order 2 + 0 = 2, the same as the stress tensor, taking one vector and returning another 1 + 1 = 2.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The $\varepsilon _{ijk}$ -symbol, mapping two vectors to one vector, would have order 2 + 1 = 3.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The collection of tensors on a vector space and its dual forms a tensor algebra, which allows products of arbitrary tensors.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Simple applications of tensors of order 2, which can be represented as a square matrix, can be solved by clever arrangement of transposed vectors and by applying the rules of matrix multiplication, but the tensor product should not be confused with this.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] There are several notational systems that are used to describe tensors and perform calculations involving them.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Ricci calculus is the modern formalism and notation for tensor indices: indicating inner and outer products, covariance and contravariance, summations of tensor components, symmetry and antisymmetry, and partial and covariant derivatives.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The Einstein summation convention dispenses with writing summation signs, leaving the summation implicit.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Any repeated index symbol is summed over: if the index i is used twice in a given term of a tensor expression, it means that the term is to be summed for all i.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Several distinct pairs of indices may be summed this way.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Penrose graphical notation is a diagrammatic notation which replaces the symbols for tensors with shapes, and their indices by lines and curves.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] It is independent of basis elements, and requires no symbols for the indices.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The abstract index notation is a way to write tensors such that the indices are no longer thought of as numerical, but rather are indeterminates.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This notation captures the expressiveness of indices and the basis-independence of index-free notation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A component-free treatment of tensors uses notation that emphasises that tensors do not rely on any basis, and is defined in terms of the tensor product of vector spaces.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] There are several operations on tensors that again produce a tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The linear nature of tensors implies that two tensors of the same type may be added together, and that tensors may be multiplied by a scalar with results analogous to the scaling of a vector.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] On components, these operations are simply performed component-wise.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] These operations do not change the type of the tensor; but there are also operations that produce a tensor of different type.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The tensor product takes two tensors, *S* and *T*, and produces a new tensor, *S* ⊗ *T*, whose order is the sum of the orders of the original tensors.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] When described as multilinear maps, the tensor product simply multiplies the two tensors, i.e., $(S\otimes T)(v_{1},\ldots ,v_{n},v_{n+1},\ldots ,v_{n+m})=S(v_{1},\ldots ,v_{n})T(v_{n+1},\ldots ,v_{n+m}),$ which again produces a map that is linear in all its arguments.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Tensor contraction is an operation that reduces a type (*n*, *m*) tensor to a type (*n* − 1, *m* − 1) tensor, of which the trace is a special case.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] It thereby reduces the total order of a tensor by two.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The operation is achieved by summing components for which one specified contravariant index is the same as one specified covariant index to produce a new component.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Components for which those two indices are different are discarded.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For example, a (1, 1)-tensor $T_{i}^{j}$ can be contracted to a scalar through $T_{i}^{i}$ , where the summation is again implied.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] When the (1, 1)-tensor is interpreted as a linear map, this operation is known as the trace.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The contraction is often used in conjunction with the tensor product to contract an index from each tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The contraction can also be understood using the definition of a tensor as an element of a tensor product of copies of the space *V* with the space *V*∗ by first decomposing the tensor into a linear combination of simple tensors, and then applying a factor from *V*∗ to a factor from *V*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In a vector space with an inner product (also known as a metric) *g*, the term contraction is used for removing two contravariant or two covariant indices by forming a trace with the metric tensor or its inverse.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For example, a (2, 0)-tensor $T^{ij}$ can be contracted to a scalar through $T^{ij}g_{ij}$ (yet again assuming the summation convention).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] When a vector space is equipped with a nondegenerate bilinear form (or *metric tensor* as it is often called in this context), operations can be defined that convert a contravariant (upper) index into a covariant (lower) index and vice versa.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A metric tensor is a (symmetric) (0, 2)-tensor; it is thus possible to contract an upper index of a tensor with one of the lower indices of the metric tensor in the product.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This produces a new tensor with the same index structure as the previous tensor, but with lower index generally shown in the same position of the contracted upper index.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This operation is quite graphically known as *lowering an index*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Conversely, the inverse operation can be defined, and is called *raising an index*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This is equivalent to a similar contraction on the product with a (2, 0)-tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This *inverse metric tensor* has components that are the matrix inverse of those of the metric tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Important examples are provided by continuum mechanics.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The stresses inside a solid body or fluid are described by a tensor field.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The stress tensor and strain tensor are both second-order tensor fields, and are related in a general linear elastic material by a fourth-order elasticity tensor field.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In detail, the tensor quantifying stress in a 3-dimensional solid object has components that can be conveniently represented as a 3 × 3 array.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The three faces of a cube-shaped infinitesimal volume segment of the solid are each subject to some given force.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The force's vector components are also three in number.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Thus, 3 × 3, or 9 components are required to describe the stress at this cube-shaped infinitesimal segment.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Within the bounds of this solid is a whole mass of varying stress quantities, each requiring 9 quantities to describe.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] If a particular surface element inside the material is singled out, the material on one side of the surface will apply a force on the other side.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In general, this force will not be orthogonal to the surface, but it will depend on the orientation of the surface in a linear manner.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This is described by a tensor of type (2, 0), in linear elasticity, or more precisely by a tensor field of type (2, 0), since the stresses may vary from point to point.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The concept of a tensor of order two is often conflated with that of a matrix.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Tensors of higher order do however capture ideas important in science and engineering, as has been shown successively in numerous areas as they develop.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This happens, for instance, in the field of computer vision, with the trifocal tensor generalizing the fundamental matrix.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The field of nonlinear optics studies the changes to material polarization density under extreme electric fields.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The polarization waves generated are related to the generating electric fields through the nonlinear susceptibility tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] If the polarization **P** is not linearly proportional to the electric field **E**, the medium is termed *nonlinear*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Here $\chi ^{(1)}$ is the linear susceptibility, $\chi ^{(2)}$ gives the Pockels effect and second harmonic generation, and $\chi ^{(3)}$ gives the Kerr effect.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This expansion shows the way higher-order tensors arise naturally in the subject matter.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The properties of tensors, especially tensor decomposition, have enabled their use in machine learning to embed higher dimensional data in artificial neural networks.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This notion of tensor differs significantly from that in other areas of mathematics and physics, in the sense that a tensor is the same thing as a multidimensional array.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Abstractly, a tensor belongs to tensor product of spaces, each of which has a fixed basis, and the dimensions of the factor spaces can be different.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Thus, an example of a tensor in this context is a rectangular matrix.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Just as a rectangular matrix has two axes, a horizontal and vertical axis to indicate the position of each entry, a more general tensor has as many axes as there are factors in the tensor product to which it belongs, and an entry of the tensor is referred to be a tuple of integers.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The various axes have different dimensions in general.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The vector spaces of a tensor product need not be the same, and sometimes the elements of such a more general tensor product are called "tensors".
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For example, an element of the tensor product space *V* ⊗ *W* is a second-order "tensor" in this more general sense, and an order-*d* tensor may likewise be defined as an element of a tensor product of *d* different vector spaces.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A type (*n*, *m*) tensor, in the sense defined previously, is also a tensor of order *n* + *m* in this more general sense.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The concept of tensor product can be extended to arbitrary modules over a ring.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The notion of a tensor can be generalized in a variety of ways to infinite dimensions.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] One, for instance, is via the tensor product of Hilbert spaces.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Another way of generalizing the idea of tensor, common in nonlinear analysis, is via the multilinear maps definition where instead of using finite-dimensional vector spaces and their algebraic duals, one uses infinite-dimensional Banach spaces and their continuous dual.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Tensors thus live naturally on Banach manifolds and Fréchet manifolds.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Suppose that a homogeneous medium fills **R**3, so that the density of the medium is described by a single scalar value *ρ* in kg⋅m−3.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] where the Cartesian coordinates *x*, *y*, *z* are measured in m.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The numerical value of the density *ρ* must then also transform by 100−3 m3/cm3 to compensate, so that the numerical value of the mass in kg is still given by integral of $\rho \,dx\,dy\,dz$ .
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Such a quantity that scales by the reciprocal of the absolute value of the determinant of the coordinate transition map is called a scalar density.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] To model a non-constant density, *ρ* is a function of the variables *x*, *y*, *z* (a scalar field), and under a curvilinear change of coordinates, it transforms by the reciprocal of the Jacobian of the coordinate change.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] For more on the intrinsic meaning, see *Density on a manifold*.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] In general, any tensor multiplied by a power of this function or its absolute value is called a tensor density, or a weighted tensor.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] An example of a tensor density is the current density of electromagnetism.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Under an affine transformation of the coordinates, a tensor transforms by the linear part of the transformation itself (or its inverse) on each index.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] These come from the rational representations of the general linear group.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] But this is not quite the most general linear transformation law that such an object may have: tensor densities are non-rational, but are still semisimple representations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] The transformation law for a tensor behaves as a functor on the category of admissible coordinate systems, under general linear transformations (or, other transformations within some class, such as local diffeomorphisms).
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This makes a tensor a special case of a geometrical object, in the technical sense that it is a function of the coordinate system transforming functorially under coordinate changes.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Examples of objects obeying more general kinds of transformation laws are jets and, more generally still, natural bundles.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] When changing from one orthonormal basis (called a *frame*) to another by a rotation, the components of a tensor transform by that same rotation.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] This transformation does not depend on the path taken through the space of frames.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] However, the space of frames is not simply connected (see orientation entanglement and plate trick): there are continuous paths in the space of frames with the same beginning and ending configurations that are not deformable one into the other.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] It is possible to attach an additional discrete invariant to each frame that incorporates this path dependence, and which turns out (locally) to have values of ±1.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] A spinor is an object that transforms like a tensor under rotations in the frame, apart from a possible sign that is determined by the value of this discrete invariant.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Spinors are elements of the spin representation of the rotation group, while tensors are elements of its tensor representations.
[src:continuum-mechanics/tensor] Other classical groups have tensor representations, and so also tensors that are compatible with the group, but all non-compact classical groups have infinite-dimensional unitary representations as well.
